text: Soft palate cancer, also known as oral cavity cancer or squamous cell carcinoma of the soft palate, is a type of cancer that occurs in the soft palate, which is a part of the mouth. The soft palate is located at the back of the mouth and helps with breathing and speaking. Malignant tumor of the soft palate refers to a cancerous growth or tumor in this area. It's important to note that while there may be other types of cancer that can affect the soft palate, this specific term refers to squamous cell carcinoma of the soft palate.

Holocarboxylase synthetase deficiency is a type of multiple carboxylase deficiency, which refers to the condition where there is an insufficiency in one or more enzymes involved in the metabolism of amino acids. Biotin-(propionyl-CoA-carboxylase) ligase deficiency and Multiple carboxylase deficiency - neonatal onset are alternative names for this condition. It mainly affects infants and can lead to a range of developmental delays, feeding difficulties, and other health issues if left untreated.

Acute vascular insufficiency of the intestine, also known as acute gastrointestinal tract (GIT) vascular insufficiency, is a medical condition that occurs when there is a lack of blood flow to the digestive organs. This can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, cramping, diarrhea, vomiting, and nausea. Acute intestinal ischemia is another name for this condition, and it refers specifically to the blockage or narrowing of blood vessels that supply the intestines. Acute vascular insufficiency of the intestine can be a serious condition that requires prompt medical attention.

Scarlet fever is an acute, contagious disease caused by Group A beta-hemolytic streptococcus bacteria. It primarily affects the throat and skin, causing symptoms such as sore throat, fever, headache, and a characteristic red rash that spreads from the face to other parts of the body. Scarlet fever is typically treated with antibiotics and can be prevented through good hygiene practices, including frequent handwashing and avoiding close contact with those who are infected.

Upper gum cancer, also known as malignant tumor of the upper gingiva or malignant tumour of the upper gum, is a type of gum cancer that affects the tissue in the upper jaw that supports the teeth. It is a rare form of head and neck cancer, with a higher incidence in men than women. The primary treatment for upper gum cancer is surgical removal of the affected tissue, along with radiotherapy to kill any remaining cancer cells. In some cases, chemotherapy may also be used as part of the treatment regimen. Early detection and proper treatment are essential in ensuring the best possible outcome for patients.

Gum cancer, also known as gingival cancer or oral cavity cancer, refers to the development of malignant (cancerous) cells in the gum tissue. The exact synonyms for gum cancer include:

1. Malignant Gingival Tumor
2. Malignant Neoplasm of Gum
3. Malignant Neoplasm of Other Sites of Gum
4. Malignant Tumor of Gum
5. Malignant Tumour of Gingiva

Herpetic whitlow, also known as Herpetic felon, is a type of herpes simplex infection that occurs on the fingers, toes, and thumbs. It is caused by the intersection of Human herpesvirus 1 and Human herpesvirus 2, which leads to the development of lesions, fever, and swollen lymph nodes. This condition can cause symptoms such as enlarged lymph nodes, fever, and skin lesions on the fingers, toes, or thumb.

Peyronie's disease is a condition characterized by the development of scar tissue in the penis, which can lead to curvature and indentation. It is also known as Induratio penis plastica or Peyronie disease.

Oral cavity cancer is a type of gastrointestinal system cancer that occurs in the oral cavity, which is the area where the mouth and throat meet. It can include the lips, tongue, cheeks, roof of mouth, and gums. The exact synonym for oral cavity cancer is "malignant neoplasm of floor of mouth." This type of cancer can be caused by factors such as tobacco use, excessive alcohol consumption, poor diet, and exposure to the human papillomavirus (HPV). Early detection and treatment are crucial for a successful outcome.

recurrent hypersomnia is a sleep disorder characterized by recurring bouts of excessive daytime sleepiness and drowsiness. It can affect a person's ability to perform daily activities and may also be accompanied by other symptoms such as slow-moving movements, weakness, and difficulty concentrating. It is important for individuals with this condition to seek medical attention and receive proper treatment to manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.

Diplegia of the upper limbs is a type of nervous system disease that affects the movement and coordination of the arms, hands, wrists, elbows, and shoulders. It can cause weakness, stiffness, and limited mobility in these areas.

Diplegia of the upper limbs is also known as hemiplegia, which refers to a one-sided paralysis affecting either the left or right side of the body. In some cases, diplegia of the upper limbs can be caused by injury or trauma to the nervous system, such as a stroke or head injury. However, it can also be a congenital condition that is present at birth due to genetic factors or other causes.

Treatment for diplegia of the upper limbs may include physical therapy, occupational therapy, and assistive devices such as splints or wheelchairs. Medications may also be prescribed to help manage symptoms such as pain or muscle spasms. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to repair damaged nerves or improve blood flow to affected areas of the body.

Overall, diplegia of the upper limbs can be a challenging condition that requires ongoing treatment and support. However, with the right care and assistance, individuals with this condition can learn to cope with their limitations and lead fulfilling lives.

Morbilli is indeed an exact synonym of measles. Both terms refer to the same viral infectious disease caused by the Measles virus, which can spread through contact with respiratory droplets or direct contact with mucous membranes or skin lesions of an infected individual. The symptoms of measles include fever, cough, coryza (runny nose), conjunctivitis (red eyes), and a characteristic rash that starts on the face and spreads to other parts of the body.

Hodgkin's lymphoma (also known as Hodgkin disease) is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. Lymphocytic depletion, also known as lymphocyte depletion, is a condition that occurs in some cases of Hodgkin's lymphoma where a significant number of white blood cells (lymphocytes) are missing from the patient's blood. This can make it difficult for the body to fight off infections and other diseases.

Lymphocytic depletion is usually treated with chemotherapy, which can help to increase the number of lymphocytes in the patient's blood. In some cases, a stem cell transplant may also be recommended to replace any damaged or missing cells with healthy ones. It's important to work closely with your doctor to determine the best treatment plan for you based on your specific case of Hodgkin's lymphoma and other factors such as your overall health and personal preferences.

The nervous system is a complex network of nerves, ganglia, and sensory receptors that coordinate the body's movements, sensations, and internal functions. It includes the brain, spinal cord, and all other neural elements such as nerves, ganglia (clusters of neurons), and receptors.
A nervous system disease refers to a condition affecting any part of this complex network, including the central or peripheral nervous system. Nervous system diseases can be classified into various categories based on their causes, mechanisms, or pathological features. Some common examples include:
1. Traumatic brain injury (TBI) - caused by a blow or jolt to the head, which can result in damage to the brain's structure and function.
2. Stroke - occurs when blood flow is disrupted to the brain, leading to cell death and potential long-term damage.
3. Multiple sclerosis - an autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system, causing inflammation, demyelination, and eventual nerve damage.
4. Parkinson's disease - a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by the progressive loss of dopaminergic neurons in the brain.
5. Alzheimer's disease - a progressive neurological disorder that affects memory, thinking, and behavior due to the buildup of abnormal protein deposits in the brain.
6. Epilepsy - a chronic condition characterized by recurrent seizures caused by abnormal electrical activity in the brain.
These are just a few examples, but there are countless other nervous system diseases that can affect an individual's physical and cognitive abilities.

Upper lip cancer is a type of lip cancer that occurs on the upper lip, which is the part of the face above the upper teeth. It can also refer to cancer of the skin or mouth tissue in this area. The specific cause of upper lip cancer is not always clear, but it may be linked to factors such as exposure to sunlight, smoking, and certain viruses. Symptoms may include a lump or swelling on the upper lip, changes in the appearance of the skin or mouth, and difficulty moving the jaw or tongue. If you have any of these symptoms, it is important to see a doctor for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.

Chronic intestinal vascular insufficiency, also known as chronic mesenteric ischemia (CMI), is a medical condition that occurs when the blood vessels that supply the intestines become narrowed or blocked. This can lead to a lack of blood flow to the affected area and may cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, and diarrhea.

Chronic mesenteric ischemia (CMI) is a type of bowel obstruction that occurs when the blood vessels in the intestines become narrowed or blocked, leading to a lack of blood flow and potential damage to the intestinal tissue. This can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, bloating, diarrhea, and constipation.

It is important for individuals with chronic intestinal vascular insufficiency or CMI to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms and prevent complications. Treatment may include medications, lifestyle changes, and, in some cases, surgery.

Prostate carcinoma in situ, also known as high-grade prostatic intraepithelial neoplasia (HGPIN), is a precancerous condition of the prostate gland. It is characterized by abnormal cell growth within the glandular tissue of the prostate.

Prostate carcinoma in situ is considered to be one step below invasive cancer, but it still has the potential to progress to a more advanced stage if left untreated. Therefore, it is important for individuals with HGPIN to undergo regular monitoring and possibly further treatment depending on their specific case.

In summary, prostate carcinoma in situ is a type of in situ carcinoma that occurs within the prostate gland and can progress to more advanced stages if left untreated.

Uvula cancer refers to a type of soft palate cancer that originates in the uvula, which is a small projection of tissue at the back of the mouth that helps with speech and swallowing. This condition can cause difficulty speaking, breathing, and swallowing due to obstruction caused by the tumor. Malignant Uvular Tumor and malignant tumor of uvula are alternative names for this type of cancer. If you have any concerns about Uvula cancer or would like more information, please consult a medical professional.
That is correct. Phlebitis is a type of vein disease characterized by inflammation in the affected vein. It can cause symptoms such as swelling, pain, and skin discoloration.
Hodgkin's paragranuloma is a type of Hodgkin's lymphoma. Hodgkin's paragranuloma has the exact synonym Hodgkin paragranuloma.

Duodenitis is an inflammation of the duodenum, which is the first part of the small intestine. It can cause symptoms like abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. Hemorrhagic duodenitis is a specific type of duodenitis that is characterized by bleeding in the lining of the stomach or duodenum. This can cause black, tarry stools and make it difficult for blood to clot. It is often caused by long-term use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and can be treated with medications to stop the bleeding and prevent further damage to the stomach or duodenum.

Tongue cancer, also known as malignant neoplasm of the tongue, is a type of oral cavity cancer. It occurs when cells in the tongue develop abnormalities and grow uncontrollably, forming a tumor. The exact location of tongue cancer is on the tongue, which is a muscular organ that helps with taste, speech, and swallowing.

vasculitis is a type of vascular disease that occurs when the blood vessels become inflamed. It can affect arteries, veins, and capillaries, and can cause a range of symptoms depending on which vessels are affected. Treatment options may include medications to reduce inflammation and prevent blood clots, as well as lifestyle changes to manage the condition.

Hodgkin's granuloma is a specific type of Hodgkin's lymphoma, which is characterized by the presence of abnormal Reed-Sternberg cells. These cells are large and have a high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, giving them a distinctive appearance under a microscope.
Hodgkin's granuloma can also be referred to as Hodgkin's lymphoma, which is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. It is most commonly found in the upper part of the body and is more common in men than women. Treatment options for Hodgkin's granuloma typically involve chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of both.
Hodgkin's Lymphoma, Mixed Cellularity is a type of Hodgkin's Lymphoma. Hodgkin's Lymphoma, Mixed Cellularity has exact synonym Hodgkin's disease, mixed cellularity.

Chickenpox, also known as varicella, is a viral infectious disease caused by the human herpesvirus 3. It is characterized by symptoms such as fever, headache, nausea, anorexia, myalgia, and blisters on the skin. The disease can be transmitted through direct contact with secretions from the rash or by droplet spread of respiratory secretions. Chickenpox has a material basis in human alphaherpesvirus 3 and is defined as an infectious disease that results in infection located in skin. It is also known as MESH:D002644.

vein disease is a specific type of vascular disease that affects the veins. It occurs when the blood flow in the veins is obstructed, leading to swelling and inflammation in the affected area. Vein disease can occur due to various factors such as genetics, aging, or lifestyle habits like smoking or lack of physical activity. Treatment options for vein disease include surgery, minimally invasive procedures, and lifestyle changes to improve blood circulation.

postcricoid region cancer, also known as malignant tumor of the pharyngoesophageal junction, is a type of hypopharynx cancer that occurs in the area where the pharynx and esophagus meet. It is characterized by the uncontrolled growth and spread of abnormal cells, which can lead to various symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, hoarseness, and pain or pressure in the neck or throat. The exact synonyms for this cancer are malignant postcricoid region tumor and malignant tumor of pharyngoesophageal junction. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience these symptoms or have concerns about your risk for developing hypopharynx cancer. Early detection and treatment can greatly improve the chances of a successful outcome.

Lip carcinoma in situ (also known as leukoplakia) is a precancerous condition where abnormal cells are found in the lip lining. It is considered the earliest stage of lip cancer and can progress to invasive squamous cell carcinoma if left untreated. Lip carcinoma in situ has a high risk of recurrence, so it's essential to remove it completely with surgery or other treatments like radiation therapy or laser therapy.

aryepiglottic fold cancer is a type of cancer that affects the aryepiglottic fold, which is a part of the hypopharynx. The hypopharynx is the area below the larynx and above the trachea, and it plays an important role in breathing and speaking. Aryepiglottic fold cancer is also known as malignant neoplasm of the hypopharyngeal aspect of aryepiglottic fold or malignant tumor of the aryepiglottic fold - hypopharyngeal aspect. It is considered a type of head and neck cancer, and it can be treated with surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these treatments.

maxillary sinus cholesteatoma is a type of paranasal sinus disease characterized by the inflammation and infection of the maxillary sinus, which can lead to the formation of a cavity or pocket filled with cheese-like debris. It typically occurs when there is a blockage in the eustachian tube that causes the buildup of ear wax and other debris, leading to inflammation and infection. Cholesteatoma can also occur as a result of trauma or injury to the maxillary sinus.

Eating disorders are a complex group of conditions that can affect a person's emotions, thoughts and behavior in relation to food. They can cause significant distress and problems with an individual's physical health. There are several types of eating disorders, including anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, binge eating disorder, pica (eating non-food items), and rumination disorder.

Viral exanthem refers to a group of skin diseases caused by viruses. These illnesses typically present with a skin rash or eruption, and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as fever, headache, and joint pain. Examples include roseola (exanthem subitum), measles, and rubella. It is important to note that viral exanthems are contagious and can spread through close contact or respiratory droplets. If you suspect you or someone you know has a viral exanthem, it is recommended to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Alcoholic gastritis is a condition where the stomach lining becomes inflamed due to excessive alcohol consumption. It can lead to symptoms such as abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and blood in the stool. It is important to avoid alcohol to prevent worsening of the condition. If you suspect you have alcoholic gastritis, it is recommended to speak with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Myeloid sarcoma is a type of hematologic cancer that refers to the malignant transformation of pluripotent myeloid cells, which are responsible for producing various types of blood cells. It can be characterized by the presence of a large number of immature white blood cells, including granulocytes and monocytes, in the bone marrow or peripheral blood. The exact synonyms for Myeloid sarcoma include Chloroma, Extramedullary Myeloid tumor, Granulocytic sarcoma, and Synovial sarcoma with prominant myeloid cell contanct. It is important to note that Myeloid sarcoma can be locally invasive or metastatic and may require different treatment options compared to other types of leukemia or lymphoma.

skin carcinoma in situ is a type of skin cancer, and it refers to a precancerous condition where the cancer cells are confined to the epidermal layer of the skin. It is characterized by abnormal cell growth and division without invasion into deeper layers of tissue. The exact synonym for skin carcinoma in situ is cutaneous carcinoma in situ, and it can be further related to carcinoma in situ of skin.

Tonsillar pillar cancer is a type of oropharynx cancer that originates in the tonsillar pillars, which are the two small masses of tissue located on either side of the throat above the tonsils. The exact synonyms for this type of cancer are malignant neoplasm of tonsillar pillar and malignant tumor of tonsillar pillar. It is also referred to as malignant neoplasm of tonsillar pillars, posterior.

That is correct. Cholesteatoma is a type of keratosis that occurs when the skin in the middle ear or mastoid becomes thickened and inflamed. It can lead to the buildup of keratin, a protein found in skin cells, which causes further irritation and inflammation. The condition typically affects people with eustachian tubes that are blocked or malformed, making it difficult for them to equalize the pressure in their middle ear. Cholesteatoma can cause hearing loss, ringing in the ears (tinnitus), and even deafness if left untreated. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have cholesteatoma so that it can be properly diagnosed and treated.

Mycosis fungoides is a type of primary cutaneous T-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma. It is a slow-growing form of cancer that mainly affects the skin, but can also spread to other parts of the body. The exact synonym for Mycosis fungoides is "Mycosis fungoides lymphoma."

Myeloid leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells. It is characterized by the overproduction of abnormal myeloid cells, which can lead to anemia, infections, and easy bleeding. There are different subtypes of myeloid leukemia, including acute myeloid leukemia (AML) and chronic myeloid leukemia (CML). Treatment options may vary depending on the specific type and stage of the disease.

That is correct. Neuropathy, also known as peripheral neuropathy, is a type of nervous system disease that affects the peripheral nerves or nerve cells, typically leading to symptoms such as pain, numbness, and weakness in the extremities.

Cheek mucosa cancer, also known as buccal mucosa cancer, is a type of oral cavity cancer that arises from the mucosal lining of the cheek. The exact synonym for this condition is malignant neoplasm of the buccal mucosa. It can be further specified as malignant neoplasm of the inner aspect of the cheek or malignant neoplasm of the buccal mucosa. Additionally, it can be referred to as a malignant tumor of the buccal mucosa.

Genital herpes is a type of herpes simplex that results in infection located in the genital system, or rectum. It has a material basis in either Human herpesvirus 1 or Human herpesvirus 2 and is transmitted by sexual contact. The infection causes sores, fever, and swollen glands as symptoms. Other exact synonyms for genital herpes include Genital herpes simplex, Herpes Genitalis, Virus-Genital Herpes, and venereal herpes.

Neurofibromatosis is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the nerves and skin. It can cause tumors to grow on the nerves, skin, and other parts of the body. There are different types of neurofibromatosis, such as von Recklinghausen's disease and schwannomas. It is usually diagnosed through a physical examination and genetic testing. Treatment options depend on the type and severity of the condition but may include surgery, radiation therapy, or medications to manage symptoms.

Decubitus ulcer, also known as pressure sore or bed sore, is a type of chronic wound that develops on areas of the body that are subjected to prolonged pressure, such as bony prominences. It results from the prolonged application of force over an area of skin and underlying tissue, causing localized ischemia (lack of blood flow) and eventually necrosis (death of tissue). Decubitus ulcer can occur in various parts of the body but is most common on the lower backside, tailbone, heels, and hips. It can be painful and may lead to long-term complications if not treated properly. Early detection and intervention are crucial for effective management and prevention of decubitus ulcer.

in situ carcinoma is a type of pre malignant neoplasm, meaning it is a cancer that has not yet spread to other parts of the body. It is defined as a carcinoma that is in its early stages of development and has not invaded surrounding tissues.

Yes, that's correct. Vascular dementia is a type of dementia that is caused by problems with blood vessels in the brain, leading to impairments in cognitive function. It is also known as multi-infarct dementia and multifocal dementia.

The term "milker's nodule" refers to a viral infectious disease that affects cattle and humans, caused by the Pseudocowpox virus. It is transmitted through contact with infected cow teats or via fomites. The infection results in skin lesions on the fingers, hands, and forearms, accompanied by fever, lymphangitis, and lymphadenopathy. The disease has exact synonyms such as "Milkers' node," "Paravaccinia," and "milker nodule." It is related to the Pseudocowpox virus.

anaerobic pneumonia is a type of aspiration pneumonia, which is characterized by anaerobic bacterial infection. Symptoms may include fever, chills, cough, shortness of breath, and chest pain. It can also lead to the formation of lung abscess or empyema. Diagnosis is typically made through a combination of clinical presentation, radiographic findings, and culture results. Treatment usually involves antibiotics targeted against anaerobic bacteria, such as penicillin G, metronidazole, or tetracycline.

Carotid body cancer, also known as malignant paraganglioma or vascular neoplasm of the carotid body, is a rare type of cancer that originates from the para-aortic and pre-aortic areas surrounding the bifurcation of the common carotid artery. These tumors are characterized by an encapsulated, firm round mass, which can cause local symptoms such as facial swelling, neck pain or a pulsating sensation in the affected area.

Carotid body cancer is considered a type of vascular cancer because it arises from the blood vessels and not from other types of cells. It is also classified as malignant when it has invaded surrounding tissues or spread to distant organs, such as the lungs or brain.

In summary, carotid body cancer is a rare type of vascular cancer that originates from the para-aortic and pre-aortic areas surrounding the bifurcation of the common carotid artery. These tumors are characterized by an encapsulated, firm round mass and can cause local symptoms such as facial swelling, neck pain or a pulsating sensation in the affected area.

Smallpox is a viral infectious disease that results in infection located in skin, has\_material\_basis\_in Variola virus, which is transmitted by droplets from oral, nasal or pharyngeal mucosa, transmitted by contact with the body fluids, or transmitted by fomites. The infection results in formation of lesions, first on the face, hands and forearms and later on the trunk.

Leukoplakia of the penis is a precancerous condition characterized by thick, white or gray patches on the skin of the penis. It is caused by prolonged exposure to the human papillomavirus (HPV). Treatment typically involves removing the affected tissue with surgery or other methods. Prevention can be achieved through regular screenings and practicing safe sex.

Bacterial pneumonia is a type of bacterial infection that occurs when harmful bacteria infect the lungs, leading to inflammation and potentially serious illness. It can be caused by various species of bacteria, including Streptococcus pneumoniae, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, and Legionella pneumophila. Symptoms may include coughing, chest pain, fever, shortness of breath, and fatigue. Bacterial pneumonia can be treated with antibiotics, and in severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have bacterial pneumonia or any other type of pneumonia.

Seborrheic dermatitis is a type of inflammatory skin condition that results in flaky, white to yellowish scales on oily areas such as the scalp or inside the ear. It is caused by an overproduction of skin oil and irritation from yeast Malassezia furfur. The symptoms include itching, skin lesions, scales, redness, plaques and hair loss.

Erythema infectiosum, commonly known as Fifth disease, is a viral infection caused by the parvovirus B19. It results in a red rash on the face and other parts of the body. The symptoms can include fever, headache, joint pain, and swollen glands.

text: Gastric mucosal hypertrophy is a condition in which the lining of the stomach becomes thickened. It can be caused by chronic gastritis, and it is characterized by the presence of large, rugal folds that extend into the depths of the stomach. These folds are called giant rugal hypertrophy, and they can cause the stomach to become enlarged over time. Gastric mucosal hypertrophy is also sometimes referred to as Menetrier disease or familial giant hypertrophic gastritis. It can be a serious condition that may require medical treatment, such as the use of medications to reduce stomach acid production or surgery to remove excess tissue.

Pyomyositis is a type of inflammatory myopathy that affects the muscles and is commonly found in tropical and subtropical regions. It is characterized by the sudden onset of pain, swelling, and tenderness in the affected muscle groups, and can be caused by a variety of factors such as infections, autoimmune disorders, or trauma. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have pyomyositis, as it can lead to long-term complications if left untreated.

acute myeloid leukemia (AML) is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood. It is characterized by the uncontrolled production of abnormal white blood cells, which can lead to anemia, infections, and easy bleeding. AML can be classified into two main types: acute promyelocytic leukemia (APL) and acute megakaryocytic leukemia.

Acute megakaryocytic leukemia is a subtype of AML that involves the proliferation of large numbers of megakaryocytes, which are cells in the bone marrow that give rise to platelets. These patients often have low levels of platelets in their blood and may experience excessive bleeding or bruising. In addition, acute megakaryocytic leukemia can cause bone pain and swelling due to the accumulation of abnormal megakaryocytes in the bone marrow.

AML is generally considered a serious disease, and treatment options may vary depending on the specific subtype and extent of the cancer. Common treatments for AML include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, stem cell transplantation, and targeted therapies. With advances in research and treatment, the outlook for AML patients has been improving over time. However, it is still crucial to seek medical attention promptly if you experience symptoms of AML or have concerns about your blood cells or bone marrow.

contagious pustular dermatitis is a type of skin disease.
contagious pustular dermatitis is a type of viral infectious disease.
contagious pustular dermatitis is a type of something that at least has material basis in some orf virus.
contagious pustular dermatitis is a type of something that at least transmitted by contact transmission and vehicle borne fomite transmission.
contagious pustular dermatitis is a type of disease with location on skin.
contagious pustular dermatitis has definition A viral infectious disease that results_in infection located_in skin, has_material_basis_in Orf virus, which is transmitted_by contact with infected or recently vaccinated animals, or transmitted_by fomites carrying the virus. The infection has symptom lesions on the finger, hand, arm, face, and penis..
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym Ecthyma contagiosum.
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym Ecthyma, Contagious.
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym Orf.
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym scabby mouth.
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym sheep pox.
contagious pustular dermatitis has exact synonym thistle disease.

Crohn's disease is a type of inflammatory bowel disease that affects the intestines. It is characterized by chronic inflammation in the lining of the intestine and can also involve other parts of the gastrointestinal tract, such as the stomach and the small intestine. Crohn's disease can lead to a variety of symptoms, including abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, vomiting, and weight loss. It can also cause complications, such as fistulas and abscesses, which can require surgery to treat. There is no cure for Crohn's disease, but it can be managed with medications and dietary changes.

Rubella, also known as German measles, is a viral infectious disease that results from infection with the Rubella virus. The virus is transmitted through droplet spread of oronasal secretions from an infected person, and it can also be transmitted congenitally. The symptoms of rubella include a rash on the face that spreads to the trunk and limbs, fever, lymphadenopathy, joint pains, headache, and conjunctivitis.

text: disseminated chorioretinitis is a type of chorioretinitis.

Breast carcinoma in situ, also known as non-infiltrating carcinoma of the breast or carcinoma in situ of the breast, is a type of breast cancer that is confined to the breast and has not spread to other parts of the body. It is characterized by the abnormal growth of cells within the breast tissue, which can lead to the development of tumors. In some cases, it may progress to invasive carcinoma, but with proper treatment, it can be effectively managed and the risk of progression can be minimized.

Eye carcinoma in situ, also known as carcinoma in situ of the eye or CISE, is a type of eye cancer that is characterized by the growth of abnormal cells on the surface of the eye. It is considered to be a precancerous condition and can progress to invasive squamous cell carcinoma if left untreated.
CISE typically affects older adults and is more common in men than women. It can cause symptoms such as redness, irritation, and discharge from the eye, as well as vision changes. Early detection and treatment are essential to prevent progression to invasive cancer and preserve vision.
lung carcinoma in situ is a type of cancer that forms in the lining of the air passages within the lung. It is also known as "precancerous" because it is an early stage of lung cancer development.

trachea carcinoma in situ is a type of cancer that occurs in the trachea, which is a part of the respiratory system. It is also referred to as tracheal carcinoma in situ or carcinoma in situ of the trachea.

:intermediate_coronary_syndrome rdfs:subClassOf :coronary_artery_disease ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Angina at rest"@en,
        "Anginal chest pain at rest"@en,
        "Impending infarction"@en,
        "Preinfarction angina"@en,
        "Unstable angina"@en,
        "Worsening angina"@en .
text: Intermediate coronary syndrome, also known as Prinzmetal's angina, is a type of coronary artery disease that occurs when the small vessels in the heart are narrowed or blocked. This can lead to chest pain or discomfort, especially during physical activity or rest. The symptoms may include tightness, pressure, or a burning sensation in the chest, as well as shortness of breath, nausea, and fatigue. Intermediate coronary syndrome is considered more serious than stable angina because it is often caused by a complete obstruction of a coronary artery. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you experience these symptoms to avoid a heart attack. Treatment options may include medications such as nitrates, beta blockers, and calcium channel blockers, as well as procedures such as angioplasty or bypass surgery. Lifestyle changes, such as quitting smoking, eating a healthy diet, and exercising regularly, can also help to reduce the risk of developing coronary artery disease.

Heterophyiasis is a type of parasitic infection called helminthiasis. It involves the intestinal infection by the parasite Heterophyes, which can lead to symptoms such as diarrhea and colicky abdominal pain. If left untreated, migration of the eggs to the heart can result in fatal myocardial and valvular damage, and the brain may also be infected. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you have this disease in order to receive proper treatment.

Colon carcinoma in situ, also known as stage 0 colon cancer or intestinal carcinoma in situ of the colon, is a type of colonic disease characterized by the presence of abnormal cells within the inner lining of the colon. It is considered to be a precancerous condition, which means that it may progress to invasive colon cancer if left untreated.

Colon carcinoma in situ can occur throughout the length of the colon, from the rectum to the sigmoid colon, and may involve the entire thickness of the inner lining of the colon. It is often found incidentally during routine screening tests such as a colonoscopy or sigmoidoscopy, and treatment may include surgical removal of the affected area.

In summary, colon carcinoma in situ is a precancerous condition that can progress to invasive colon cancer if left untreated. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal cells within the inner lining of the colon, and it may involve the entire thickness of the inner lining. Treatment typically involves surgical removal of the affected area.

Parasitic helminthiasis is a type of infectious disease caused by the presence of parasitic worms in the body. These worms can include species such as cestodes, nematodes, and trematodes. The exact synonyms for Parasitic helminthiasis are Helminth infection, Helminthiasis, Helminthosis, and Worm infection.

That is correct. Hodgkin's lymphoma, nodular sclerosis is another way of referring to the same type of cancer. It is also known as Classical Hodgkin lymphoma with nodular sclerosis. This type of cancer is characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells and can be treated with chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of both.

Metagonimiasis is a type of parasitic infection caused by the roundworm Metagonimus yokogawai. It primarily affects the intestines and can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain and diarrhea. The disease has a location in the intestine, and it can also infect other organs like the heart and brain. It is an example of a helminthiasis, which is a type of parasitic infectious disease.

Sublingual gland cancer is a type of salivary gland cancer that occurs when malignant cells grow and spread in the sublingual gland. It has the same name as the intersection of three other types of cancer: breast, lung, and ovarian cancer. This specific cancer has the definition of a malignant tumor of the sublingual gland, which is a part of the salivary gland system that produces saliva. The exact synonym for this type of cancer is "malignant tumor of the Sublingual gland."
fascioliasis is a type of bile duct disease.

Salivary gland cancer, also known as malignant neoplasm of salivary gland, is a type of oral cavity cancer that arises from the cells of the salivary gland. It refers to the abnormal growth and spread of cancer cells in the salivary gland, which can lead to various symptoms such as swelling or lumps in the neck, difficulty swallowing, hoarseness, and pain. It is important to note that this type of cancer can be diagnosed using imaging tests like CT scans, biopsies, and other diagnostic procedures. Early detection and prompt treatment are crucial for effective management of salivary gland cancer.

Lupus erythematosus is an autoimmune disease that affects the musculoskeletal system, characterized by a constellation of symptoms including elevated antibodies to nuclear antigens, antiphospholipids, low complement levels, ulcers, non-scarring alopecia, renal or neurologic damage, and low white blood cell and platelet counts. It also has symptoms related to affected organs such as rashes, fatigue, arthritis, hair loss, seizures, and symptoms related to the kidneys and brain.

Tonsil cancer is a type of oropharynx cancer, which is a malignant neoplasm of the faucial tonsil, palatine tonsil or tonsil, faucial. It can also be referred to as malignant Tonsillar tumor or simply tonsil cancer. The exact synonym for this type of cancer is "tonsil cancer."

:pulmonary_subvalvular_stenosis rdfs:subClassOf :pulmonary_valve_stenosis ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Congenital Infundibular Stenosis"@en,
        "Infundibular pulmonic stenosis"@en,
        "Infundibular pulmonic stenosis, congenital"@en,
        "Subvalvular pulmonic stenosis"@en,
        "pulmonary infundibular stenosis"@en .
text: Subvalvular pulmonic stenosis, also known as congenital infundibular stenosis or infantile subaortic stenosis, is a narrowing of the blood vessels (specifically, the aortic and/or pulmonary valve) in the heart. It occurs when the valves do not fully open, causing increased pressure in the blood vessels and potentially leading to hypertension or heart failure if left untreated. Subvalvular pulmonic stenosis can be diagnosed through echocardiography and treated with surgery, often before a child is born. It's important to seek medical attention as soon as possible for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Acute monocytic leukemia, also known as acute monoblastic leukemia or AML M5, is a type of leukemia characterized by the rapid proliferation of abnormal monocytes in the bone marrow. These cells do not mature and are unable to perform their normal functions in the body. As a result, the number of normal blood cells, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets, decreases significantly.

Symptoms of acute monocytic leukemia can include fever, fatigue, easy bruising or bleeding, weakness, joint pain, and swelling in the legs and feet. Treatment typically involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, bone marrow transplantation, and sometimes stem cell transplantation.

It is important to note that while there are no specific dietary recommendations for acute monocytic leukemia, a healthy diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats can support the immune system and help maintain overall health during treatment. It is also important to consult with a healthcare professional regarding any specific dietary needs or restrictions.

Actinic keratosis, also known as solar keratosis or senile hyperkeratosis, is a common skin condition characterized by the formation of thick, scaly patches on sun-exposed areas of the body. It is considered a pre-malignant lesion, meaning that it can progress to skin cancer if left untreated. The exact synonyms for actinic keratosis are solar keratosis and senile hyperkeratosis.

Molluscum contagiosum is a type of viral infectious disease that results from infection with the Molluscum contagiosum virus. The virus has a material basis and is transmitted by contact or fomites, leading to skin lesions that are flesh-colored with a pit in the center.

Neuromyelitis optica (NMO) is a rare autoimmune disorder that primarily affects the central nervous system, including the optic nerve and spinal cord. It is characterized by inflammation of these structures, which can lead to symptoms such as vision loss, pain, weakness, and difficulty with coordination or balance. NMO can also cause demyelination in the spinal cord, which may result in paralysis or other neurological symptoms. The exact cause of NMO is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be triggered by an abnormal immune response against the optic nerve and/or the spinal cord. There are different subtypes of NMO, including those associated with certain genetic markers or other environmental factors. In some cases, NMO can also affect the peripheral nervous system. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of clinical examination, laboratory tests, and imaging studies such as MRI or CT scans. Treatment may include corticosteroids, plasma exchange, or other immunosuppressive medications, depending on the severity of the disease and individual patient factors.

Penis carcinoma in situ, also known as Bowen's disease of the penis and Queyrat's erythroplasia, is a type of in situ carcinoma that is located within the penis. It is characterized by abnormal cell growth within the skin or mucous membranes of the penis, which can potentially progress to invasive carcinoma if left untreated. Penile intraepithelial neoplasia grade III, also known as carcinoma in situ of the penis, is another term used to describe this condition. Symptoms may include changes in the appearance or texture of the skin or mucous membranes of the penis, such as redness, scaling, or thickening, as well as discharge or bleeding from the penis. Early detection and treatment are crucial for effective management and reducing the risk of progression to invasive carcinoma.

fasciolopsiasis is a parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease that is caused by infection with the Fasciolopsis buski parasite. It affects the intestine and can cause a range of symptoms, including diarrhea, abdominal pain, fever, ascites, anasarca, and intestinal obstruction.

Rosacea is a chronic skin disorder that typically affects the face, particularly the cheeks and nose. It causes redness, pimples, and swelling on the surface of the skin. In some cases, it can also cause eye problems. Here are some common symptoms:
1. Facial redness or flushing
2. Swollen blood vessels (broken capillaries) on the face
3. Small, pus-filled bumps or cysts on the skin
4. Pimples or blackheads
5. Sensitive skin that may feel hot or irritated
6. In some cases, rosacea can cause eye problems such as redness, tearing, and discomfort. Here are some natural remedies to help alleviate the symptoms of rosacea:
1. Avoid triggers: Common trigger foods that may cause a flare-up include spicy or acidic foods, alcohol, caffeine, and hot beverages. Identify your personal triggers and try to avoid them.
2. Use gentle skin care products: Choose non-comedogenic skincare products that are free from fragrances, dyes, and sulfates. Look for moisturizers with niacinamide or ceramides, which can help soothe and protect the skin.
3. Exercise regularly: Regular exercise can help reduce inflammation in the body and improve blood flow to the skin, which may help alleviate rosacea symptoms.
4. Practice relaxation techniques: Stress and anxiety can exacerbate rosacea symptoms. Try deep breathing exercises, meditation, or yoga to help you relax and manage your stress levels.
5. Seek medical advice: If your rosacea is severe or does not respond to home remedies, consult a dermatologist for prescription medications that can help treat the condition.

Lower lip cancer is a type of lip cancer, which refers to the growth of abnormal cells in the lower lip region. This type of cancer can occur when the cells in the lining of the lips and mouth undergo mutations or changes that cause them to grow uncontrollably. It can be caused by various factors such as smoking, sun exposure, and certain viruses. Early detection and proper treatment are crucial in preventing complications and achieving a successful recovery. If you have any concerns about lower lip cancer or other types of cancer, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional for personalized advice and guidance.

Chorioretinitis is an inflammatory eye condition that affects the choroid layer of the eye and may involve the retina as well. It can cause symptoms such as pain, redness, and blurry vision. Retinochoroiditis is a specific type of chorioretinitis that involves only the retinochoroidal blood vessels.

Pityriasis rosea is a skin condition characterized by an initial large, round spot on the chest, abdomen or back, known as a herald patch. This is followed within a week by a distinctive pattern of similar but smaller papules on the torso, arms and legs. The exact synonym for pityriasis rosea is Pityriasis circinata.

Psoriasis is a type of autoimmune disease characterized by the rapid growth of skin cells. This leads to the formation of thick, scaly patches on the skin. It can also affect the joints and other organs in the body. Psoriasis has a genetic component, and it can be triggered or exacerbated by environmental factors such as sunlight, stress, and certain medications. Treatment options for psoriasis include topical creams, oral medications, and phototherapy.

:mitochondrial_encephalomyopathy rdfs:subClassOf :mitochondrial_myopathy .
text: mitochondrial encephalomyopathy is a type of mitochondrial myopathy.

Progressive Myoclonus Epilepsy (PME) is a type of variable age at onset electroclinical syndrome. It is characterized by its relentlessly progressive disease course until death, and it has the exact synonyms PME and Progressive Myoclonic Epilepsy. This condition also has an exact match with NCI:C7636.

tinea nigra is a type of superficial mycosis that affects the skin. It's characterized by brown to black macules on the palmar aspects of hands and sometimes other surfaces of the skin. It's caused by Hortaea werneckii, a common saprophytic fungus found in humid tropical and sub-tropical regions.

Dermatophytosis is a type of cutaneous mycosis, which refers to the presence of fungal infections on the skin. It is caused by various types of fungi belonging to the Ascomycota group, particularly those known as dermatophytes. These fungi have the ability to utilize keratin, a protein found in hair and nails, as a nutrient source, and are able to infect the skin through minor cuts or abrasions. Dermatophytosis can occur on any part of the body but is most commonly seen on the scalp, glabrous skin (skin without hair), and nails. It is important to seek medical treatment for dermatophytosis to prevent the spread of infection and promote healing.

Leukoplakia of the vagina is a precancerous condition characterized by the presence of white, thickened tissue that cannot be easily rubbed off. This condition increases the risk of developing into cancer if left untreated. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Skin melanoma is a type of skin cancer that occurs when the cells responsible for producing melanin, called melanocytes, become abnormal and start to grow uncontrollably. It can develop on any part of the body, but commonly appears on areas exposed to the sun such as the face, neck, arms, legs, and back. The risk of developing skin melanoma increases with age and exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or tanning beds. Early detection and treatment are essential in reducing the risk of death from this cancer.

autoimmune thrombocytopenic purpura (ATP) is a type of primary thrombocytopenia in which the body's immune system attacks and destroys platelets, leading to a decrease in the number of platelets in the blood. This condition is also known as immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) or idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP).
ATP can cause bruising and bleeding due to the low number of platelets, and it can be a serious condition if left untreated. Treatment options for ATP include medications that suppress the immune system, such as corticosteroids, or other medications that increase platelet production, such as romiplostim or eltrombopag.

text: primary thrombocytopenia is a type of autoimmune disease of blood.

Learning disability, also known as learning disorder or academic skill disorder, is a neurological disorder that affects an individual's ability to learn and process information. It can manifest in various ways, such as difficulties with reading, writing, spelling, reasoning, memory recall, or organization of information. The exact synonym for learning disability is "academic skill disorder" or simply "learning disorder."

That is correct, atrophic gastritis is a condition where the stomach lining becomes thinner due to long-term acid reflux. It can lead to a decrease in the production of hydrochloric acid and pepsin, which are essential for proper digestion. The symptoms of atrophic gastritis may include indigestion, bloating, nausea, and abdominal pain. In some cases, it can also lead to atrophy of the stomach muscles and an increased risk of stomach ulcers. Treatment options for atrophic gastritis typically involve reducing acid reflux through dietary changes and medication, and in some cases, surgery may be necessary.

Wilson disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to metabolize copper. It occurs when there is an excess of copper in the liver, brain, and corneas of the eyes, which can cause damage to these tissues and organs over time. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, fatigue, tremors, and difficulty walking or coordination.

There are two forms of Wilson disease: hepatocellular and neurologic. Hepatocellular Wilson disease primarily affects the liver and can cause jaundice, cirrhosis, and liver failure if left untreated. Neurologic Wilson disease primarily affects the nervous system, leading to symptoms such as tremors, rigidity, and difficulty walking.

Treatment for Wilson disease typically involves medications to remove excess copper from the body and prevent further accumulation. Lifestyle changes may also be recommended to help manage symptoms. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you or someone you know has Wilson disease, as it can lead to serious complications if left untreated.
Retromolar area cancer is a type of oral cavity cancer that occurs in the area behind the molars. It is also known as malignant tumor of retromolar area.

Plantar fascial fibromatosis is a connective tissue disease that causes progressive thickening and fibrosis in the palmar fascia, leading to symptoms such as early painless nodules, decreased range of motion, weakened grip, and eventually contracture. It has the exact synonyms of Dupuytren's contracture of the foot and Ledderhose's disease.

Waldeyer's ring cancer, also known as oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma, is a type of head and neck cancer that affects the area around the tonsils and tongue. It is caused by the uncontrolled growth of cells in the mucosal lining of the oropharynx, which is part of the throat.

The exact cause of Waldeyer's ring cancer is not well understood, but it is believed to be linked to factors such as smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, and a weakened immune system. Early detection through regular screenings, such as oral examinations and biopsies, can improve the chances of successful treatment and recovery.

Treatment options for Waldeyer's ring cancer may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and/or targeted therapy. The most appropriate treatment approach will depend on the stage and location of the cancer, as well as the patient's overall health and personal preferences.

It is important to note that Waldeyer's ring cancer can be a serious condition, but with early detection and proper treatment, the chances of successful recovery are generally good.

Seborrheic infantile dermatitis is a type of seborrheic dermatitis that affects the scalp of newborn infants. It is caused by an overgrowth of a fungus called Malassezia furfur and can be associated with immune system disorders. The symptoms include thick, crusty, yellow or brown scales on the scalp. It is also known as cradle cap.

Lattice corneal dystrophy is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the cornea. It is characterized by recurrent erosions and lattice line refractile and fleck-like opacification located in the cornea, amyloid deposits beginning in the anterior stroma, and progressive vision loss later in life. The disease has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation of transforming growth factor beta-induced gene located in chromosome 5q31.1, which encodes keratoepithelin. Abnormalities in this protein lead to increased amyloid protein deposition and disruption of the corneal surface. Lattice corneal dystrophy is also known as familial amyloid neuropathy, Finnish type.

Severe nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy (NPDR) is a stage of the eye condition called diabetic retinopathy. NPDR occurs when the small blood vessels in the retina become damaged and leak fluid, which can cause swelling and eventually lead to vision loss if left untreated. It is considered severe when the blood vessels are severely narrowed or blocked, causing increased pressure within the eye. High risk nonproliferative diabetic retinopathy (HR-NPDR) is another term for NPDR that has been used in the past. However, it is now preferred to use the term "severe NPDR" instead of HR-NPDR to describe this stage of the disease.

diabetic retinopathy is a chronic diabetes-related disease that affects the blood vessels in the retina, which can lead to vision loss if left untreated. It is commonly referred to as Retinal abnormality - diabetes-related. The condition can be caused by high sugar levels over an extended period of time and is more common in people with type 2 diabetes. Early detection and treatment are crucial to prevent the progression of the disease and preserve vision.

sideroblastic anemia is a type of aplastic anemia, which is characterized by the bone marrow's inability to produce red blood cells (erythrocytes). In sideroblastic anemia, the bone marrow produces ringed sideroblasts instead. The term "Anemia Sideroblastic" or "Anemia, hypochromic with iron loading" are other synonyms for this condition.

Cowpox is a viral infectious disease that primarily affects cows and rodents, but can also be transmitted to humans through direct contact with an infected animal. It causes the formation of vesicopustular lesions on the hands or face. The exact synonym for Cowpox is "Yaba".

Metal metabolism disorder is a type of inborn error, where the body is unable to process and utilize certain minerals due to a genetic defect. This can lead to various health problems if left untreated. The symptoms and severity of metal metabolism disorders vary depending on which metal is involved and how severe the defect is. Treatment may involve dietary changes, medication, or other therapies to manage the symptoms and prevent complications.
Tonsillar fossa cancer is also known as malignant neoplasm of the tonsillar fossa, which is a type of oropharynx cancer. Another synonym for this condition is malignant tumor of the tonsillar fossa.

Yes, Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis is a type of viral infectious disease that results from infection with the measles morbillivirus. It is characterized by inflammation and degeneration of the brain, leading to severe neurological symptoms and ultimately fatality if left untreated. The condition has a material basis in the measles virus, which is immune-resistant. The exact synonyms for this disease include Immunosuppressive measles encephalitis, Van Bogaert's sclerosing leukoencephalitis, and subacute sclerosing leukoencephalopathy.

autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by the presence of multiple cysts located in the kidney resulting from ciliopathy that disrupts the function of primary cilium, inherited in an autosomal dominant fashion.

Narcolepsy is a sleep disorder that affects a person's ability to control their sleep-wake cycles. It is characterized by excessive daytime sleepiness and a sudden onset of deep sleep, which can occur at any time of the day or night. People with narcolepsy may also experience cataplexy, a loss of muscle tone that can lead to falls while they are asleep or awake. In some cases, people with narcolepsy may also have paroxysmal sleep, which is a sudden onset of deep sleep that can occur during the day or night. It is important for individuals with narcolepsy to work with their healthcare provider to manage their symptoms and ensure they are getting enough quality sleep.

Choledochal cyst is a type of bile duct disease that is characterized by the dilation of one or more extrahepatic or intrahepatic bile ducts. It can also be referred to as congenital choledochal cyst, bile duct cyst, or biliary cyst.

Cervix Uteri Carcinoma In Situ is a precancerous condition of the cervix, characterized by abnormal cell growth and alterations in the tissues of the uterus. It is also known as CIN III, severe dysplasia of the cervix, carcinoma in situ of the cervix, or carcinoma of the cervix stage 0. The exact synonyms for this condition include:

* Severe dysplasia of the cervix
* Carcinoma in situ of the cervix
* Carcinoma of the cervix stage 0
* Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia grade III with severe dysplasia
* Squamous intraepithelial neoplasia, grade III.
It is important to note that while Cervix Uteri Carcinoma In Situ can be a precursor to invasive cervical cancer if left untreated, it is highly treatable when detected early and managed properly through procedures such as loop electrosurgical excision procedure (LEEP) or cone biopsy.

Polycythemia vera is a type of myeloproliferative neoplasm, which is characterized by the overproduction of red blood cells in the bone marrow. It also causes an increase in white blood cells, platelets and a large spleen. The exact synonyms for Polycythemia vera include Osler-Vaquez syndrome, Polycythaemia rubra vera, Proliferative polycythaemia and chronic erythremia.
degenerative disc disease is a type of bone deterioration disease that has material basis in gradual dehydration and tears located in intervertebral disk.

:hepatopulmonary_syndrome rdfs:subClassOf :liver_disease .
text: hepatopulmonary syndrome is a type of liver disease.

Sudden infant death syndrome (SIDS) is a term used to describe the sudden and unexpected death of an infant under one year of age that remains unexplained after a thorough investigation. It is also known as crib death, cot death, or SUID (sudden unexpected infant death). It is important to note that while the exact cause of SIDS is unknown, there are several risk factors that have been identified, including:

* Being male: Boys are at a higher risk than girls.
* Age: Infants between 1 and 4 months of age are at the highest risk.
* Socioeconomic status: Infants from low-income families are at higher risk.
* Premature birth: Infants who were born prematurely are at a higher risk.
* Smoking during pregnancy: If one or both parents smoke, the risk of SIDS increases.
* Overheating: Being too hot can increase the risk of SIDS.

It is important to create a safe sleep environment for infants by ensuring that they sleep on their backs, in a separate crib or bassinet, and with minimal bedding and soft objects. This can help reduce the risk of SIDS. If you have any concerns about your baby's sleep, it is recommended to consult with your pediatrician.

Psoriatic arthritis is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the skin and connective tissue. It is characterized by joint inflammation, which often occurs in combination with psoriasis. The exact synonyms for this condition include arthritis psoriatica, arthropathic psoriasis, and psoriatic arthropathy.

Liver lymphoma, also known as Lymphoma of the Liver, is a type of cancer that affects the liver. It occurs when the lymphocytes in the liver become cancerous and begin to multiply uncontrollably. There are different types of liver lymphoma, including diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, which is the most common type, and primary central nervous system lymphoma, which affects the brain or spinal cord.

Liver lymphoma can cause a variety of symptoms, such as abdominal pain, fever, fatigue, weight loss, and jaundice. It is often diagnosed through blood tests and imaging techniques like CT scans or MRI. Treatment for liver lymphoma typically involves a combination of chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and/or surgery, depending on the stage and extent of the cancer.

It's important to note that while there are similarities between liver lymphoma and other types of lymphoma, they are distinct diseases with different causes, risk factors, and treatment approaches. If you have concerns about liver lymphoma or any other health issues, it's always best to consult with a qualified healthcare professional.

Larynx carcinoma in situ (also known as stage 0 carcinoma of the larynx) is a type of cancer that has developed in the inner lining of the larynx, also known as the squamous cell carcinoma. This type of cancer is considered to be non-invasive and has not spread beyond the lining of the larynx. It is typically treated with surgery or radiation therapy to remove the affected area.

Esophageal leukoplakia is a pre-cancerous condition that affects the lining of the esophagus. It is characterized by the presence of white or yellow patches on the mucosa, which can be caused by chronic irritation, such as gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), or long-term exposure to hot or acidic substances. The condition may also be associated with a weakened immune system and smoking. In some cases, esophageal leukoplakia can progress to more serious forms of cancer, such as squamous cell carcinoma, if left untreated. Therefore, it is important for individuals with this condition to seek medical attention and undergo regular screenings to monitor its progression.

intestine carcinoma in situ is a term used to describe the early stages of cancer development that occurs within the walls of the intestines. It refers specifically to the abnormal growth of cells that are not normal and have the potential to become malignant. Intestine carcinoma in situ can be found in various parts of the gastrointestinal tract, including the colon, rectum, stomach, small intestine, and esophagus. It is also referred to as a precancerous condition because it has the potential to progress into full-blown cancer if left untreated. The term "in situ" means "in place," so in this case, it refers to cancer that is still confined to its original location and has not spread to other organs or tissues.

Gastrointestinal lymphoma, also known as gastric lymphoma or mucosal-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma, is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that affects the gastrointestinal system. It typically begins in the stomach or small intestine and may spread to other parts of the body if left untreated. Gastrointestinal lymphoma is caused by an overgrowth of abnormal white blood cells called B-cells, which are a type of lymphocyte. These cells can accumulate in the gastrointestinal tract and cause inflammation or cancerous cells to develop. Treatment options for gastrointestinal lymphoma include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery, depending on the stage and extent of the disease.

Parotid gland cancer, also known as malignant neoplasm of the parotid or malignant tumor of the parotid, is a type of salivary gland cancer that occurs in the parotid gland. It is a rare form of head and neck cancer, accounting for less than 5% of all cases. The exact cause of parotid gland cancer is unknown, but it may be linked to certain risk factors such as exposure to radiation, smoking, and genetics. Symptoms include swelling or a lump on the face near the ear, difficulty opening the mouth, and jaw pain. Treatment options for parotid gland cancer may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, and/or targeted therapy, depending on the stage of the cancer and other factors.

Polyp of the corpus uteri, also known as an endometrial polyp or uterine polyp, is a non-cancerous growth that occurs in the lining of the uterus. These polyps can vary in size and may cause symptoms such as heavy bleeding, abnormal bleeding, pain, and cramping. However, they are generally benign and do not spread to other parts of the body.

It is essential for women to consult a healthcare professional if they experience any of these symptoms or if they suspect that they have a polyp in their uterus. Early detection and treatment can help prevent complications such as infertility, miscarriage, or even cancer.

In addition to medical treatments, some lifestyle changes may also be helpful for women with polyps of the corpus uteri. For instance, reducing caffeine intake, avoiding excessive alcohol consumption, and maintaining a healthy diet rich in fruits and vegetables can contribute to overall health and wellness.

In conclusion, while polyp of the corpus uteri is not cancerous, it is crucial for women to seek medical attention if they experience any concerning symptoms or suspect that they may have this growth. Additionally, making lifestyle changes such as reducing caffeine intake and maintaining a healthy diet can help improve overall wellness.

Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix is a type of cervical disease.
Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix has definition A cervical disease characterized by the presence of a hyperkeratotic lesion..
Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix has exact synonym Uterine cervix leukoplakia.
Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix has exact synonym Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix uteri.
Leukoplakia of the uterine cervix has exact synonym Cervical leukoplakia..

Zellweger syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple organ systems in the body, primarily the liver, spleen, and lungs. It is caused by a deficiency or absence of functional peroxisomes, which are small organelles found in most cells that play an important role in metabolism. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that to be affected, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene - one from each parent. Symptoms can include liver and spleen enlargement, poor feeding, jaundice, hearing loss, and vision problems. Treatment options may include vitamin supplementation, dietary modifications, and medications to manage complications.

bladder carcinoma in situ is a specific type of cancer that affects the urinary bladder. It is also known as an in situ carcinoma, which means it has not yet spread to other parts of the body. Bladder carcinoma in situ usually starts with precancerous cells in the lining of the bladder, and if left untreated, these cells can develop into a more invasive form of cancer known as invasive bladder cancer. It is important to catch and treat this type of cancer early on to prevent it from progressing further.

Peroxisomal disease refers to a group of rare, inherited metabolic disorders that affect the peroxisome, which are small organelles found in most cells. The primary function of peroxisomes is to break down fats and other lipids into smaller molecules like glycerol and fatty acids. In individuals with a peroxisomal disease, one or more of these enzymes responsible for breaking down fats are either missing, faulty, or overproduced, leading to the accumulation of abnormal fatty acids and their derivatives in various tissues of the body. This can result in a wide range of symptoms depending on which specific enzyme is affected and which organs are involved. Common symptoms include developmental delays, vision problems, movement disorders, and/or intellectual disability. Some peroxisomal diseases can also cause acute episodes of severe illness, such as vomiting, fever, and liver or kidney failure, particularly in infants and young children. There is currently no cure for most peroxisomal diseases, but early diagnosis and appropriate treatment can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

Exactly. Pityriasis versicolor is a common skin condition that can affect people of all ages, but it's more likely to occur in warm and humid climates or during the summer months. The fungus responsible for this condition, Malassezia furfur, thrives in these conditions. It causes a superficial mycosis, characterized by well-demarcated white, pink, fawn, or brownish lesions that often coalesce and are covered with thin, furfuraceous scales. The condition can be diagnosed through skin scrapings and lab tests, and it can be treated with topical medications such as antifungal creams or shampoos. It's important to practice good hygiene and avoid sharing personal items like towels or clothing to prevent the spread of this fungus.

Ritter's disease, also known as Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome (SSS), is a rare and severe bacterial infection caused by the toxin produced by a type of Staphylococcus bacteria called S. aureus. It primarily affects newborn infants, but can also occur in older children and adults with weakened immune systems. The symptoms include widespread erythema (redness), fluid-filled blister formation, fever, irritability, and skin peeling. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you suspect that you or a loved one may have Ritter's disease, as it requires prompt treatment with antibiotics and other supportive measures.

Leishmaniasis is a parasitic protozoa infectious disease caused by the parasite Leishmania. It can be transmitted through the bite of sandflies (subfamily Phlebotominae). The symptoms and severity of leishmaniasis depend on the specific species of the parasite and the part of the body affected. Post-Kala-Azar Dermal Leishmaniasis is a type of leishmaniasis that occurs after Kala-Azar, an infectious disease caused by the sandfly bite.
Liver fibroma is a type of liver benign neoplasm. It is also known as Fibroma of the Liver.

Lethal midline granuloma is a type of nose disease characterized by the inflammation and destruction of the tissues in the nasal passages. It can cause significant damage to the structure and function of the nose, leading to breathing difficulties, discomfort, and other complications.
Midfacial Necrotising Lesion is another name for Lethal midline granuloma, as well as malignant granuloma of face. These terms are used interchangeably to describe this type of nose disease. It is important to note that Lethal midline granuloma can be a serious and potentially life-threatening condition if left untreated. If you suspect you have this condition, it is crucial to seek medical attention immediately.
Disseminated Lupus Erythematosus.

Macroglobulinemia is a condition in which there are abnormally high levels of a protein called macroglobulin in the blood. It can also be referred to as primary macroglobulinemia when it is not caused by any other underlying medical conditions.

anal carcinoma in situ is a type of in situ carcinoma that occurs when abnormal cells grow and multiply without normal differentiation, potentially leading to cancer. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal cells within the anal canal's epithelial layers, which may be precancerous or cancerous. Anal carcinoma in situ typically affects older adults and those with a history of anogenital warts or human papillomavirus (HPV) infection. It is usually diagnosed through a biopsy or a visual examination, such as a colonoscopy. Treatment options may include surgical removal of the affected tissue, laser therapy, or radiation therapy. Early detection and treatment are crucial to prevent the spread of cancer and improve patient outcomes.
