text: parapsoriasis is a type of psoriasis.

Sleep behavior disorder, also known as REM sleep behavior disorder, is a condition characterized by abnormal behaviors during sleep, such as acting out violent or dramatic dreams with rapid eye movement (REM). This can lead to potential harm to oneself or others. It is important for individuals with this disorder to seek medical attention and follow proper treatment recommendations to manage their symptoms effectively.

Esophagus carcinoma in situ, also known as severe esophageal dysplasia, is a precancerous condition that affects the esophagus. It is characterized by abnormal cells in the mucosa layer of the esophagus. These abnormal cells have the potential to become cancerous if left untreated.
Esophagus carcinoma in situ can be diagnosed through endoscopy, which allows doctors to visualize the inside of the esophagus and identify any abnormalities. Treatment for esophagus carcinoma in situ typically involves surgery or other forms of therapy to remove the affected tissue.
It is important to note that while esophagus carcinoma in situ is a serious condition, it is often curable when treated early and properly. Regular screenings and check-ups can help detect this condition early on, allowing for timely treatment and improved outcomes.

Erythematosquamous dermatosis is a skin condition characterized by the presence of reddish-brown patches on the skin, often accompanied by itching and scaling. It can be caused by various factors such as exposure to harsh sunlight, dry air, or chemicals. Treatment typically involves using topical creams or ointments to reduce inflammation and promote healing of the affected areas. In more severe cases, oral medications may be prescribed. It's important to consult a dermatologist for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Sebaceous gland disease, also known as acne vulgaris, is a skin condition where the sebaceous glands become inflamed due to an excess of oil production. It occurs when the pores in the skin become clogged with oil and dead skin cells, causing bacteria to grow and leading to pimples or blackheads. Acne can affect people of all ages, but it is most common during adolescence when hormones are more active. Treatment options include topical creams, antibiotics, and other medications that help to control oil production and reduce inflammation. Additionally, maintaining proper skin care habits such as washing your face twice a day with soap and water, using sunscreen, and avoiding excessive use of oily products can prevent the development of acne.

occipital lobe neoplasm is a type of brain cancer that originates in the occipital lobe, which is located at the back of the brain. The term "neoplasm" refers to a new growth of abnormal cells, and when used in this context, it means a tumor or cancerous growth in the occipital lobe. Other synonyms for occipital lobe neoplasm include malignant neoplasm of the occipital lobe, neoplasm of the occipital lobe, and tumor of the Occipital Lobe.

Uterine cancer in situ, also known as endometrial carcinoma in situ, refers to a type of cancer that is confined to the inner lining (endometrium) of the uterus. It is a non-invasive cancer, meaning it has not spread beyond the uterine lining into surrounding tissues or organs.

Uterine cancer in situ can be further classified as endometrial intraepithelial carcinoma (EIC) and endometrioid adenocarcinoma in situ (EAIS). EIC is characterized by the presence of abnormal glandular cells, while EAIS features abnormal endometrial glands along with stroma. Both types share similar treatment options with hysterectomy or endometrial resection as the primary approach.

It's worth noting that the term "uterus carcinoma in situ" is an outdated and misleading description, as it implies a cancerous condition within the uterus. Instead, the proper term should be "uterine cancer in situ," which accurately reflects the cancer's location within the uterine lining.

Cutaneous leishmaniasis is a type of skin disease that results in one or more cutaneous lesions caused by a Leishmania species. It can be referred to as Asian Desert Cutaneous Leishmaniasis, Leproid Leishmaniasis, or Diffuse Cutaneous Leishmaniasis.

granuloma inguinale is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results in an infection located in the skin or the mucosa of the genital tract. It has a material basis in Klebsiella granulomatis and is transmitted by sexual contact or through contact with open sores. The symptoms include painless genital ulcers. Another name for this disease is donovanosis, and it can also be referred to as pudendal ulcer.

acute myeloid leukemia, also known as AML, is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells. It is characterized by the rapid growth of abnormal white blood cells that accumulate in the bone marrow and interfere with the production of normal blood cells. AML has a high death rate if not treated, so it's important to seek medical attention immediately if you or someone you know experiences symptoms such as fatigue, fever, easy bruising or bleeding, frequent infections, or abdominal pain. Treatment options may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, bone marrow transplantation, and targeted therapy.

Amyloidosis is a type of disease that occurs when an abnormal protein called amyloid accumulates in the body's tissues and organs. This can cause damage to these organs and affect their normal function. There are several types of amyloidosis, including primary and secondary forms. Primary amyloidosis is a type that occurs when the body produces too much amyloid protein, while secondary amyloidosis occurs when a plasma cell disorder causes an excess of abnormal proteins to be produced. Amyloidosis can affect various organs in the body, including the heart, kidneys, liver, and digestive system. Symptoms may include fatigue, swelling, joint pain, and confusion. Treatment options may include medications to reduce amyloid production or to help remove excess amyloid from the body.

Eczema herpeticum is a type of skin disease that is caused by the herpes simplex virus. It is characterized by the development of small, painful blisters on the skin, often accompanied by fever and swelling of the lymph nodes. The disease can affect any area of the body but is most commonly found on the face, especially around the eyes and mouth. Eczema herpeticum typically occurs in individuals who have a weakened immune system or are already suffering from an existing skin condition. Treatment options for this disease may include antiviral medications, topical creams or ointments to reduce inflammation, and keeping the affected area clean and dry.

Lower gum cancer is a type of oral cancer that affects the lower part of the gum line. It is also known as malignant tumor of the lower gingiva, and malignant tumour of the lower gum. These terms are used interchangeably to describe the same condition. Oral cancer can be caused by various factors such as smoking, alcohol consumption, and exposure to certain viruses. It is important to practice good oral hygiene habits and visit your dentist regularly for early detection and treatment of any potential issues.

A neuromuscular disease that is characterized by an abnormal reduction in the muscle volume and atrophy is known as atrophic muscular disease. It is a type of muscular disease, but it can also be classified as a neuromuscular disease since it involves the nerves and muscles. Atrophic muscular disease can affect different parts of the body, including the legs, arms, shoulders, back, and neck. The cause of atrophic muscular disease can vary depending on the specific type, but common causes include aging, genetic factors, infections, inflammation, and certain medications.

Liver carcinoma in situ (also known as liver cancer, or hepatocellular carcinoma) is a type of cancer that forms in the liver. It occurs when healthy liver cells undergo changes that cause them to grow and multiply uncontrollably, forming a tumor. These tumors can be benign (noncancerous) or malignant (cancerous). In situ carcinoma refers to a cancer that is confined to the organ in which it formed (in this case, the liver), without spreading to other parts of the body. Biliary system refers to the bile ducts and gallbladder, which are part of the liver's bile production and secretion process.

Stomach carcinoma in situ, also known as carcinoma in situ of the stomach or gastric carcinoma in situ, is a type of cancer that is located within the lining of the stomach. It is a precancerous condition, meaning it can progress to become invasive cancer if left untreated. The term "in situ" means "in its original place," so in this context, it refers to cancer that is confined to its original location in the stomach lining and has not spread to other parts of the body. It is important to note that while stomach carcinoma in situ can be treated, it is generally considered a serious condition due to the risk of progression to invasive cancer if left untreated.
Peliosis hepatis is a type of hepatic vascular disease, and it can also be referred to as hepatic peliosis.

Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of bone disease.
Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of splenic disease.
Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of liver disease.
Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of leishmaniasis.
Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of something that at least has symptom some weight loss.

Visceral leishmaniasis is a type of something that at least disease has location some liver.
Visceral leishmaniasis is a severe form of the disease caused by protozoan parasites of the Leishmania genus, resulting in the infection of the internal organs such as liver, spleen and bone marrow. The symptoms include fever, weight loss, and an enlarged spleen and liver.
Infection by visceral leishmaniasis is synonymous with Visceral Leishmaniasis.
Kala-Azar is another name for Visceral Leishmaniasis.

Hard palate cancer, also known as malignant neoplasm of the hard palate or malignant tumor of the hard palate, is a type of oral cavity cancer. It occurs in the bony structure of the roof of the mouth, specifically on the hard palate (the anterior part of the palatal shelf). This disease has the potential to spread to other parts of the body if left untreated. Early detection and proper treatment are crucial for a successful recovery. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, numbness or a feeling of heaviness in the affected area. If you suspect that you have hard palate cancer, it is important to consult with a healthcare professional as soon as possible to determine the best course of action.

Variola minor, also known as alastrim, cottonpox, milkpox or whitepox, is a mild form of smallpox that primarily affects the skin and results in the formation of lesions. It is caused by the Variola virus.

Mucocutaneous leishmaniasis is a type of Leishmaniasis that affects the mucosal surfaces of the nose, throat, and larynx. It is caused by the protozoan parasite Leishmania and can lead to severe damage and scarring in these areas. The disease has an exact synonym of American cutaneous leishmaniasis, American mucocutaneous leishmaniasis, cutaneous leishmaniasis, American, Mucocutaneous leishmaniasis, American, New World cutaneous leishmaniasis.

Gas gangrene is a type of commensal bacterial infectious disease that results in infection, located in muscle tissue, has_material_basis_in Clostridium perfringens, which produce gas that becomes trapped in the infected tissue. Gas gangrene usually develops after injuries or surgery. The infection has symptom large blisters, has symptom pain in the infected area, has symptom myonecrosis, has symptom gas production, and has symptom sepsis. It is also known as Gas bacillus infection.

Liver benign neoplasm refers to a type of non-cancerous tumor that originates in the liver. It is also known as hepatic or intrahepatic bile duct neoplasm, which specifically affects the bile ducts within the liver. These tumors are generally benign, but can cause problems if they grow large enough or press on surrounding organs. Treatment options for liver benign neoplasm may include surgical removal, ablation, or other minimally invasive procedures. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Achalasia is a type of esophageal disease characterized by an inability of the esophagus to move food toward the stomach because the lower esophogeal sphincter (LES) does not fully relax during swallowing. It is also known as achalasia of cardia, achalasia of esophagus, and hypertensive lower esophageal sphincter.

Neurotic excoriation, also known as dermatitis artefacta or factitia, is a skin condition where the individual intentionally causes harm to their own skin. This can be done through various means such as scratching, picking, rubbing, or even applying harmful substances like detergents or chemicals. The intent behind this behavior is often driven by emotional distress, anxiety, or other psychological factors.

Factitious skin disease is another term that can be used to describe this condition. It refers to the deliberate creation of skin lesions or symptoms for personal gain or attention, usually with the help of a healthcare provider. In some cases, individuals may also manipulate their environment or use medications to create skin issues.

It's important to note that neurotic excoriation is not the same as other forms of dermatitis, which are caused by external factors like allergens or irritants. While treatment for dermatitis generally focuses on addressing the underlying cause and managing symptoms, treating neurotic excoriation often involves addressing the psychological factors that contribute to the behavior. This may involve therapy, support groups, and other resources to help individuals better manage their emotional well-being.

Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome (WAS) is a rare, genetic disorder that affects the immune system and causes blood clotting problems. It is inherited in an X-linked recessive pattern, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

Liver leiomyoma is a type of non-cancerous tumor that originates in the liver. It is also known as a liver myoma or simply a hepatic leiomyoma. These tumors are made up of smooth muscle cells and are not malignant, meaning they do not have the potential to spread to other parts of the body or cause metastasis.

Liver leiomyomas are relatively uncommon, with a reported incidence rate of around 1-2% in adults. They can vary greatly in size, from just a few millimeters to several centimeters in diameter. In most cases, liver leiomyomas do not cause any symptoms and are discovered incidentally during routine imaging tests or exploratory laparoscopy for other medical conditions.

However, in some cases, liver leiomyomas can cause complications such as obstruction of bile ducts, bleeding, or pain. In these situations, surgical removal may be necessary to alleviate the symptoms and prevent further complications. Overall, while liver leiomyomas are not cancerous, they can still pose a risk to the health of an individual if left untreated or if their size significantly increases without proper management.

The term "submandibular gland cancer" refers to a type of cancer that develops in the submandibular gland, which is a salivary gland located underneath the jawbone. It is also known as malignant neoplasm of submaxillary gland or malignant tumor of the Submandibular gland. This disease can spread to other parts of the body and is considered a form of salivary gland cancer. It is important to note that this type of cancer has a location in the submandibular gland, but it's not exactly the same as intersection of something that at least disease has location some submandibular gland.

Rectum carcinoma in situ, also known as severe rectal dysplasia or carcinoma in situ of the rectum, is a precancerous condition that occurs when abnormal cells grow on the inner lining of the rectum. It is considered to be a high-risk condition because it can progress to invasive cancer if left untreated. This type of cancer typically affects people over the age of 50 and has a strong family history of colon or rectal cancer. Symptoms may include bleeding, pain during bowel movements, and a change in bowel habits. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy. It is important to consult with a healthcare professional if you have any concerns about your risk for colorectal cancer.

Liver inflammatory pseudotumor (LPP) is a benign liver tumor that arises from the liver parenchyma. LPP can also be referred to as Inflammatory Pseudotumor of the Liver. It is important to note that LPPs are not true neoplasms, but rather represent a reactive process characterized by the proliferation and accumulation of cells with fibroblast-like features. The exact cause of LPP remains unknown; however, it may be associated with certain infections or autoimmune disorders.

LPPs are typically asymptomatic and discovered incidentally during imaging studies for unrelated conditions. When symptoms do occur, they can include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, fever, and jaundice. Diagnosis is often made through a combination of imaging techniques, such as ultrasound, CT scan, or MRI. A liver biopsy may also be performed to confirm the diagnosis.

Treatment for LPP usually involves surgical resection; however, some cases may be treated with percutaneous ethanol injection or radiofrequency ablation. In cases where the LPP is too widespread for surgery, liver transplantation may be considered as an option.

It is important to note that while LPPs are generally benign and do not spread beyond the liver, they can cause significant damage if left untreated. Therefore, it is crucial to seek medical attention if you suspect you have LPP or any other liver condition.

amebiasis is a type of parasitic protozoa infectious disease. Amebiasis is caused by the amoeba Entamoeba histolytica, which invades the intestinal lining and causes dysentery, colitis or diarrhea. It can also spread through the blood to the liver and other organs. Symptoms include abdominal pain, diarrhea, fever, and vomiting. Amebiasis is treated with antibiotics and supportive care, including rehydration and electrolyte replacement. Prevention measures include proper handwashing and avoiding contact with contaminated water or food.

Pemphigus is an autoimmune disease that affects the skin and mucous membranes, causing blistering and erosion of the outer layer. It is characterized by the formation of pustules or blisters that rupture easily and leave painful wounds. The disease can cause a range of symptoms including itching, burning, and crusting of the skin, as well as difficulty swallowing and breathing in more severe cases. Treatment for Pemphigus typically involves a combination of medications to suppress the immune system and reduce inflammation, along with topical treatments to manage symptoms.

The vestibule of the mouth is a part of the oral cavity that leads to the lips and inner surfaces of the cheeks. Mouth cancer, also known as oral cavity cancer, can occur in this area when cells in the mouth develop abnormalities and grow uncontrollably, eventually forming a tumor. The term "malignant neoplasm of vestibule of mouth" and "malignant tumor of vestibule of mouth" are specific synonyms for vestibule of mouth cancer.

text: Esophageal dyskinesia, also known as oesophageal dysmotility, is a condition that affects the normal functioning of the muscles in the esophagus. This can result in difficulty swallowing, regurgitation, and food getting stuck in the chest or throat. It is estimated that around 1 in 10 people with Parkinson's disease will experience this condition. The exact cause is not known but it may be related to the effects of dopamine on the muscles in the esophagus. Treatment options include medications, therapy, and dietary changes.

Speech disorders can be classified into several types, including:

1. Articulation Disorders: These involve difficulty with the actual production of speech sounds (phonemes). Examples include lisping and stuttering.
2. Resonation Disorders: These involve problems with the vocal cords or other structures in the voice box that affect the sound of the voice. Examples include hoarseness and vocal nodules.
3. Speech Sound Disorders: These involve difficulty with the accurate production of speech sounds, often due to a disruption in brain function. Examples include Childhood Apraxia of Speech (CAS) and Dyspraxic Speech.
4. Fluency Disorders: These involve problems with the smoothness or rate of speech, such as stuttering or cluttering.
5. Voice Disorders: These involve problems with the voice itself, including issues with pitch, volume, or quality of sound. Examples include vocal nodules and muscle tension dysphonia.

Lichen planus is a chronic, autoimmune disorder characterized by the development of itchy, purple or brown skin lesions. It can affect any part of the body but is commonly found on the wrists, ankles, legs, and torso. The exact cause of lichen planus is unknown; however, it has been linked to a weakened immune system, genetic predisposition, and exposure to certain allergens or chemicals. There is no cure for lichen planus, but treatment options may include topical corticosteroids, antihistamines, phototherapy, and immunosuppressive medications. In some cases, lichen planus can be associated with other health issues such as hepatitis or kidney disease; therefore, it is important for patients to work closely with their healthcare provider to monitor and manage potential complications.

Barrett's esophagus is a type of esophageal disease characterized by the change of normal esophageal squamous epithelium to a columnar and intestinal-type epithelium. It is also known as Barrett's oesophagus, Barrett's ulcer of esophagus, and Barrett's syndrome. Additionally, it can be referred to as ulcerative esophagitis.

No, you are correct. Periodic limb movement disorder (PLMD) is indeed a type of sleep disorder characterized by involuntary movements of the upper or lower extremities during sleep. These movements can cause disturbances in the sleeper's rest and may lead to daytime fatigue or other symptoms. The term "nocturnal myoclonus" specifically refers to a similar condition, but it is not an exact synonym for PLMD as it does not necessarily involve movement of the limbs. Instead, nocturnal myoclonus can also affect other muscle groups and may not always occur during sleep.

Herpes zoster oticus is a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the facial nerve, which leads to paralysis of one side of the face. It has a material basis in human herpesvirus 3 and reactivates after appearing as chickenpox in childhood. The infection is characterized by symptoms such as vesicular rash of the ear or mouth, tinnitus, vertigo, otalgia, and headache. It can also be known by other names like geniculate herpes zoster, Herpes zoster auricularis, herpetic geniculate ganglionitis, Ramsay Hunt syndrome type 2, Ramsey Hunt syndrome, geniculate neuralgia, or nervus intermedius neuralgia.

Pityriasis rubra pilaris, also known as Devergie's disease, is a skin condition characterized by the appearance of small, red, scaly patches on the skin. These patches are usually found on the arms, legs, and torso, although they can also appear on other areas of the body. The skin may become thick and rough, and in some cases, it may cause itching or discomfort. Pityriasis rubra pilaris is typically harmless, but it can be a sign of an underlying condition such as psoriasis or eczema. If you are concerned about this condition, it is best to consult with a dermatologist for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Central sleep apnea (CSA) is a type of sleep apnea characterized by a malfunction in the central nervous system, specifically with the respiratory control center. This leads to difficulties in breathing and can cause an individual to miss one or more cycles of breathing during sleep. It is also known as central sleep apnea syndrome (CSAS).

Pompholyx is a type of sweat gland disease that causes recurring blisters on the palms, soles, and fingers. It is characterized by pruritis (itchiness) and cracked skin, and it can be triggered by exposure to certain substances or conditions. The exact synonyms for pompholyx are Cheiropompholyx, dyshidrotic eczema, vesicular eczema of hands and/or feet, and dyshidrosis.

Kidney carcinoma in situ, also known as high-grade papillary renal cell carcinoma, is a type of kidney cancer that forms in the lining of the kidneys. This type of cancer is more aggressive than other types and has a higher risk of spreading to other organs. It is typically diagnosed through imaging tests such as ultrasound or CT scan, and biopsy is often required for definitive diagnosis. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, and immunotherapy.

User, you are correct. Pyriform sinus cancer is a type of hypopharynx cancer that originates in the pyriform sinus, which is a small air-filled cavity located in the anterior part of the cranium. The term "pyriform sinus" refers specifically to this particular location within the skull.

There are several other synonyms for pyriform sinus cancer, including "malignant neoplasm of pyriform fossa" and "malignant tumor of pyriform fossa." These terms refer to the same type of cancer but may be used interchangeably in different contexts.

It's worth noting that hypopharynx cancer is a relatively rare form of head and neck cancer, accounting for only about 2% of all cases. However, it can be quite aggressive and potentially life-threatening if left untreated. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these approaches.

Erythromelalgia is a type of neuropathy characterized by intense, burning pain in the extremities. The skin around the affected area turns red and feels hot to touch. It can also cause increased sweating and tingling sensations. Erythromelalgia is rare and can be caused by various factors such as spinal cord injuries, cancer, or exposure to certain medications.

Alagille syndrome is a type of liver disease that affects the liver's ability to process bile. This condition is characterized by an accumulation of bile in the liver due to reduced number of small bile ducts. Alagille syndrome is also known as Arteriohepatic dysplasia and Alagille-Watson syndrome.

Cerebral amyloid angiopathy is a type of inherited metabolic disorder that affects the cerebrum and leads to symptoms such as spontaneous cerebral hemorrhage, ischemic lesions, and progressive dementia. It occurs due to abnormal deposits of amyloid protein in the walls of blood vessels in the brain, leading to degenerative vascular changes that can cause spontaneous bleeding in the brain. The condition has a hereditary basis and is characterized by the presence of structural variants that are involved in the production or processing of amyloid protein.

Pallister Hall Syndrome (PHS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects development. It occurs due to an inherited mutation in the GLI3 gene on chromosome 7p14. This condition is characterized by a range of physical and medical issues, such as hypothalamic hamartoma, pituitary dysfunction, central polydactyly (an extra finger or toe), visceral malformations, and intellectual disability. PHS can also impact the endocrine system, causing abnormal hormone production. The severity of symptoms in PHS patients varies greatly among individuals, with some experiencing mild symptoms while others may have more severe complications. Early diagnosis is essential for managing and treating the condition effectively.

Bemer-Langer Syndrome, also known as Type IV Short Rib Polydactyly Syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder that results in multiple congenital anomalies. These anomalies include hydrops fetalis (a condition where the fluid in the womb increases pressure and can damage organs), facial abnormalities, visceral abnormalities (problems with internal organs), short ribs, and short limbs. Bemer-Langer Syndrome is caused by mutations in the FGF3 gene, which plays a role in fetal development and growth. It is important to note that this syndrome can be life-threatening for the fetus if not detected and treated early on.

Acrocallosal syndrome is a type of digenic disease.
Acrocallosal syndrome is a type of polygenic inheritance.
Acrocallosal syndrome has material basis in some agenesis of corpus callosum.
Acrocallosal syndrome is an autosomal recessive disorder characterized by corpus callosum agenesis, polydactyly, multiple dysmorphic features, motor and mental retardation.
Schinzel syndrome 1 is another name for Acrocallosal syndrome.

Amino acid metabolic disorder is an inherited metabolic disorder where the body has difficulty processing and breaking down amino acids.
The term used to describe this condition is inborn errors of amino acid metabolism. These disorders can affect various aspects of life, including physical growth, development, behavior, and overall health. The specific symptoms depend on which amino acid is affected and how it's processed by the body. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to managing these conditions and preventing long-term complications.

    :has_exact_synonym "GANT"@en,
        "GIST"@en,
        "Stromal tumor of gastrointestinal tract"@en,

text:
Gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is a type of cancer that affects the gastrointestinal system. GIST refers to a specific subtype of intestinal tumors, characterized by the presence of particular genetic mutations. These tumors are most commonly found in the small intestine, but can also occur in other parts of the gastrointestinal tract.

GISTs can be benign or malignant, with malignant tumors being more common and potentially life-threatening if not treated promptly. Symptoms of GIST may include abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, blood in the stool, weight loss, and a palpable mass or lump in the abdomen.

Treatment for GIST depends on the size, location, and type of tumor, as well as the patient's overall health. Surgery is typically the first-line treatment option, with the goal of removing the entire tumor. In some cases, chemotherapy or targeted therapies may also be used to help destroy remaining cancer cells or to prevent the cancer from recurring.

It's important for individuals who suspect they have GIST to seek medical attention and undergo a thorough diagnostic evaluation to determine the best course of treatment. Early detection and treatment can significantly improve outcomes for people with this type of cancer.

Mast cell leukemia is a type of leukemia characterized by an overwhelming number of tissue mast cells located in the peripheral blood. It is considered a mast cell neoplasm, which means it originates from mast cells.

Frontotemporal dementia (FTD) is a type of dementia characterized by progressive neuronal loss predominantly involving the frontal and/or temporal lobes of the brain. This leads to a gradual and progressive decline in behavior, language, or both. It can also cause changes in personality and social behavior. FTD is one of the most common types of dementia in people under 60 years of age. There are several subtypes of FTD, including frontal lobe syndrome, temporal lobe epilepsy with complex partial seizures, and motor neuron disease. It's important to note that while there is no cure for FTD, treatments can help manage symptoms and improve quality of life for those affected.

Colorectal cancer is a type of large intestine cancer that occurs when abnormal cells grow and divide uncontrollably in the colon or rectum. It can also spread to other parts of the body, but it is most commonly found in the lower part of the large intestine, which includes the colon and rectum. Colorectal cancer can be prevented with regular screenings such as colonoscopies and fecal occult blood tests, and it can also be treated with surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.

Waardenburg syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by varying degrees of deafness, minor defects in structures arising from the neural crest and pigmentation anomalies of the hair, skin, and/or iris of both eyes. It has exact synonyms such as Waardenburg Shah syndrome, Waardenburg's syndrome, van der Hoeve Halbertsona Waardenburg syndrome, and narrow synonyms such as Waardenburg types I and/or II.

Nasopharynx carcinoma is a type of cancer that originates in the nasopharynx, which is the upper part of the throat located behind the nose. It is also known as nasopharyngeal carcinoma or malignant nasopharyngeal tumor. The exact synonym for Nasopharynx carcinoma is Nasopharyngeal carcinoma.

Homocystinuria is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by the accumulation of homocysteine in the blood and increased excretion in the urine. It has exact synonyms, such as CBS deficiency, cystathionine beta synthase deficiency, and cystathionine synthase deficiency.

Histidine metabolism disease is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder that occurs due to deficiency in histidine. It can lead to various health issues and disturbances in the body's ability to produce or utilize histidine properly. The exact synonym for this condition is "Disturbances of histidine metabolism."

Cystinuria is a type of ureteral disease, characterized by the formation of cystine stones in the kidneys, ureter, and bladder due to an amino acid metabolic disorder. It can also affect the urinary bladder and kidney location.

Urea cycle disorder is a genetic metabolic disorder that occurs when one or more enzymes in the urea cycle are missing or not working properly. The urea cycle is responsible for removing excess ammonia from the blood and converting it into urea, which can be eliminated through urine. When this process is impaired, ammonia levels in the blood can rise to dangerous levels, causing symptoms such as vomiting, lethargy, and even coma. Urea cycle disorder is treated with a special diet that restricts protein intake and medications to help remove excess ammonia from the body. In severe cases, dialysis or other supportive measures may be necessary.

Glycine encephalopathy is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by high levels of glycine in bodily fluids and tissues. It can cause developmental delays, seizures, and other neurological symptoms. Treatment may involve dietary restrictions, medications, and other therapies to manage the symptoms.

Maple syrup urine disease is a rare genetic disorder characterized by an accumulation of certain amino acids in the blood and urine due to a deficiency of the enzyme decarboxylase. This leads to an odor similar to maple syrup in the urine, vomiting, hypertonicity, severe mental retardation, seizures, and eventually death if left untreated. It can be diagnosed through a urine test that detects the presence of these abnormal amino acids. Treatment typically involves a strict low-protein diet to help manage symptoms and prevent further complications.

Alkaptonuria is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to process tyrosine, an amino acid found in many proteins. The accumulation of homogentisic acid, a toxic byproduct of tyrosine metabolism, causes the deposition of black pigment (melanin) in various tissues and organs, including the skin, hair, nails, eyes, and internal organs. This can lead to symptoms such as premature graying or even blackening of hair, painful bone lesions, joint problems, and kidney stones. Alkaptonuria is caused by a deficiency in the enzyme homogentisic acid 1,2-dioxygenase, which is responsible for breaking down homogentisic acid. Treatment typically involves dietary restrictions on protein and limiting the intake of foods high in tyrosine, such as red meat, chocolate, and certain dairy products. In some cases, medications may be prescribed to help manage symptoms and slow the progression of the disease.

ornithine carbamoyltransferase deficiency is a type of urea cycle disorder, where the body is unable to produce an effective form of the enzyme ornithine transcarbamylase. This leads to a build-up of ammonia in the blood and can cause symptoms such as lethargy, vomiting, seizures, and coma if left untreated. It is also known as deficiency of citrulline phosphorylase and ornithine transcarbamylase deficiency.

Citrullinemia is a type of urea cycle disorder, which is characterized by the accumulation of ammonia and other toxic substances in the blood. It occurs due to an inherited deficiency of citrulline-aspartate ligase, the enzyme responsible for converting citrulline into arginine. This leads to a build up of citrulline and imbalance in urea cycle, resulting in toxicity. Classic citrullinemia is another name for this disorder, which refers to the most common form of the condition.

Yes, you are correct. Hyperlysinemia is a rare amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by an excess of lysine in the blood due to defects in the enzymes responsible for its catabolism, such as ornithine transcarbamylase (OTC) or argininosuccinate synthetase (ASS). These enzymatic deficiencies lead to a build-up of lysine and other amino acids, which can cause various symptoms and complications depending on the severity of the condition.

Hyperlysinemia can affect many body functions, including protein metabolism, energy production, and tissue repair. Some common symptoms include growth retardation, muscle weakness, fatigue, and abnormal blood tests such as elevated lysine levels or decreased arginine levels. In severe cases, it may lead to intellectual disability and other developmental issues in infants.

Diagnosis of hyperlysinemia typically involves measuring the levels of amino acids in the blood using a specialized test called an amino acid analysis. Treatment depends on the underlying cause but often includes dietary restrictions, medications to manage symptoms, and supportive care. With proper management, individuals with hyperlysinemia can lead normal lives.
Tyrosinemia is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to process the amino acid tyrosine.

text: primary cerebellar degeneration is a type of neurodegenerative disease.

hyperargininemia is a metabolic disorder that occurs due to the deficiency of arginase, an enzyme responsible for breaking down arginine in the urea cycle. As a result, there is excess arginine in the blood, which can lead to symptoms such as vomiting, lethargy, and metabolic acidosis if left untreated. It is important to diagnose and treat this condition promptly to prevent long-term damage.

That is correct. Hyperhomocysteinemia is an amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by elevated levels of homocysteine in the blood. It can be caused by genetic or environmental factors, and it has been linked to various health conditions such as heart disease, stroke, and neurological disorders. It is important for individuals with hyperhomocysteinemia to work closely with their healthcare provider to manage this condition properly.

Carbamoyl Phosphate Synthetase I Deficiency Disease is a genetic disorder caused by the deficiency of Carbamoyl Phosphate Synthetase I enzyme. This enzyme plays a crucial role in the urea cycle, which is responsible for removing excess ammonia from the body. When this enzyme is not functioning properly, it can lead to the accumulation of ammonia in the blood, ultimately resulting in neurological damage and even death if left untreated. This disorder is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition.

Phenylketonuria (PKU) is a rare genetic disorder that affects an individual's ability to metabolize the amino acid phenylalanine. It occurs when the gene for phenylalanine hydroxylase (PAH), which converts phenylalanine into another amino acid, is mutated or nonfunctional. This leads to a buildup of phenylalanine in the body and can cause various health problems if left untreated. PKU is typically diagnosed soon after birth through newborn screening tests and requires a strict, lifelong, low-protein diet to manage symptoms and prevent long-term damage.

That is correct. Ocular hypertension, also known as open-angle glaucoma, is a condition in which the pressure inside the eye is higher than normal. It does not usually cause any symptoms until it is quite advanced and can cause permanent damage to the optic nerve and vision loss if left untreated. If you have ocular hypertension, it's important to regularly visit an eye doctor for monitoring and treatment.

borderline glaucoma is a type of glaucoma where the patient has some signs of damage to their optic nerve, but it isn't severe enough to be diagnosed as primary open-angle glaucoma. It is also known as pre-glaucoma or borderline glaucoma. The exact definition of borderline glaucoma is a condition where the patient has clinical features and risk factors that are associated with a high likelihood of developing optic atrophy secondary to glaucoma in the future. These features may include elevated intraocular pressure, retinal nerve fiber layer abnormalities, abnormal anterior chamber angles, and/or a positive family history for glaucoma without any evidence of current optic nerve atrophy.

Priapism is a medical condition characterized by persistent and prolonged erection of the penis, caused by the obstruction of blood flow. It is not considered a disease in itself, but rather a symptom of an underlying condition that affects the blood vessels. Priapism can be caused by various factors such as trauma to the genitals, certain medications, sickle cell anemia, and other medical conditions that affect blood flow. If left untreated, priapism can cause permanent damage to the penis and lead to infertility. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience persistent or prolonged erection of the penis, as it could be a sign of priapism or another underlying condition that requires treatment.

Myopathy of extraocular muscle is a specific type of myopathy that affects the muscles responsible for controlling eye movements. It's also known as external ophthalmia or nerve-deafness-muscle disease, which refers to any condition that involves both deafness and muscular weakness. Other synonyms include ophthalmoplegia, which is the paralysis of eye muscles; and myotonia congenita, which is a type of muscle stiffness or myopathy that's present at birth.

cleft lip is a type of orofacial cleft.
cleft lip is a type of lip disease.
cleft lip is a type of something that at least disease has location some lip.
cleft lip has definition An orofacial cleft that is characterized by a congenital defect in the upper lip where the maxillary prominence fails to merge with the merged medial nasal prominences..
cleft lip has exact synonym Labium leporinum.
cleft lip has exact synonym cheiloschisis.
cleft lip has exact synonym cleft lip, unilateral, complete.
cleft lip has exact synonym complete unilateral cleft lip.
cleft lip has exact synonym hare lip.

Lip disease, also known as lip cancer, is a type of mouth cancer that occurs in the lips and surrounding tissues. It is caused by the uncontrolled growth of cells in these areas, which can lead to the development of tumors or other abnormal cell growths. Lip cancer can be caused by various factors, such as exposure to harmful UV radiation from the sun, smoking, and excessive alcohol consumption. Early detection and treatment are essential for successful outcomes. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, bleeding, or a lump in the lip or mouth area. If you experience any of these symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment plan.

Myocardium cancer, also known as malignant myocardial tumor or tumor of the myocardium, is a type of heart cancer that affects the heart muscle tissue. It is characterized by the uncontrolled growth and spread of abnormal cells in the myocardium, which can lead to various complications such as chest pain, shortness of breath, and heart failure. Treatment for myocardium cancer typically includes surgery, chemotherapy, or a combination of both, depending on the stage and location of the cancer.

Language disorder, also known as Specific Language Impairment (SLI), is a type of communication disorder that affects an individual's ability to understand and/or produce language. It is characterized by significant difficulties in the acquisition or use of language, despite normal intelligence and developmental history. The specific nature of language disorder can vary greatly from person to person, but it often involves problems with grammar, vocabulary, or both.

Orbital disease is a type of bone disease that occurs in the region surrounding the eye, known as the orbit. This can include diseases affecting the bones of the orbit or the soft tissues surrounding the eye. Some examples of orbital diseases include tumors, infections, and inflammation. The location of an orbital disease may be determined by imaging studies such as CT scans or MRI. It's important to note that not all orbital diseases necessarily involve the bone directly, but rather can affect other structures within the orbit.

That is correct. Neurofibroma of the heart, also known as a neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1) tumor, is a benign growth that can occur on any part of the body, including the heart. It is caused by an abnormality in the neural crest cells, which are responsible for producing a variety of structures, such as cranial and spinal nerves, as well as other parts of the body. NF1 tumors can cause a range of symptoms depending on their size and location, including pain, swelling, or restricted movement. In some cases, they may also be associated with other health conditions such as high blood pressure or heart-related problems. Treatment for neurofibroma of the heart usually involves surgical removal of the tumor, although other options may be considered in some cases depending on the size and location of the tumor and the individual's overall health.
Splenic tuberculosis is a type of abdominal tuberculosis that results in the formation of granulomas or abscesses located in the spleen.

Rectal prolapse is a condition where the rectum, which is the last part of the large intestine that stores feces before it is eliminated from the body, drops or protrudes through the anus. It can occur due to weakened muscles in the rectum or a lack of support for the rectum by surrounding tissues.

Symptoms of rectal prolapse may include a feeling of pressure or fullness in the rectum, difficulty passing stools, and a sensation that the stool is not fully eliminated from the body after each attempt. In some cases, rectal prolapse can cause constipation or fecal incontinence, where small amounts of stool leak out of the anus without warning.

Treatment for rectal prolapse depends on the underlying cause and severity of the condition. It may involve a combination of lifestyle changes, such as eating a high-fiber diet to soften the stool and avoiding straining during bowel movements, as well as medical treatments like bulk forming agents, sphincter training exercises, or surgery in severe cases.

It's important to note that rectal prolapse can be a sign of other underlying health issues, such as inflammatory bowel disease or anal cancer, so it is best to consult with a healthcare professional if you experience symptoms of rectal prolapse.

Monieziasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease. It is characterized by the presence of Moniezia expansa, the common tapeworm of sheep, in the host's body. This infection can occur through direct contact with animals or through consuming contaminated food or water sources. Symptoms of monieziasis may include abdominal pain, diarrhea, nausea and vomiting, and weight loss. It is important for those infected to seek medical attention and undergo appropriate treatment in order to fully recover from the disease.

nasal cavity benign neoplasm is a type of respiratory system benign neoplasm that arises from the nasal cavity. It has the exact synonyms of benign nasal cavity neoplasm, neoplasm of nasal cavity, and tumor of the nasal cavity.

Chronic ethmoiditis is a type of chronic sinusitis that affects the ethmoid sinuses, which are located between the eyes. It is characterized by inflammation and swelling of the tissues in the ethmoid sinuses, which can cause pressure to build up inside the skull. This can lead to symptoms such as facial pain, headaches, and nasal congestion. Chronic ethmoiditis can last for 12 weeks or more, making it a chronic condition. It is sometimes referred to by other names, including chronic ethmoid sinusitis and ethmoidal sinusitis - chronic.

Lymphangitis is a medical condition that affects the lymphatic system. It occurs when the lymphatic channels become inflamed, usually as a result of an infection at a location distant from the affected channel. This can happen due to bacterial infections, such as those caused by Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A strep) or Staphylococcus aureus. The term "blood poisoning" is sometimes used to refer to lymphangitis, although it is not actually related to blood poisoning. Symptoms of lymphangitis may include swelling in the affected area, fever, and pain or discomfort. If left untreated, lymphangitis can lead to more serious complications, such as lymphedema or sepsis.

text: Scotoma is a type of eye disease that refers to the enlargement or contraction of the visual field, usually involving the blind spot area. The term "blind spot area" is used interchangeably with scotoma, and it is also referred to as an "enlarged angioscotoma," "enlarged blind spot," "enlarged paracaecal scotoma," or a "generalized visual field contraction or constriction." Additionally, the condition can be described as a "sector" or "arcuate visual field defect." It is important to note that while there may be other synonyms for Scotoma, these are some of the most commonly used terms in the medical community.

That is correct. Bestiality, also known as zoophilia, is a paraphilic disorder in which an individual experiences a strong sexual attraction to animals. It is important to note that while this behavior may be consensual between adults, it is generally illegal and considered highly immoral due to the potential harm and suffering it can cause to the animal involved.

A viral infectious disease is a type of disease where an infection occurs as a result of contact with a virus. These diseases can be caused by a wide range of viruses, and they often have symptoms such as fever, coughing, sneezing, and body aches. Some examples of viral infectious diseases include the common cold, the flu (influenza), and COVID-19. It's important to practice good hygiene, such as washing your hands frequently and covering your mouth when you cough or sneeze, to help prevent the spread of these types of diseases.

Taylor S Syndrome, also known as Congestion-fibrosis syndrome and Taylor Syndrome, is a type of uterine disease characterized by pelvic congestion. It occurs when the veins in the pelvic region become blocked, causing blood to pool and leading to inflammation and fibrosis (scarring) of the surrounding tissues. This can result in symptoms such as pain, swelling, and infertility. In some cases, it may also be associated with other medical conditions such as uterine cancer or endometriosis. It is important for individuals who are experiencing these symptoms to seek medical attention and receive proper diagnosis and treatment.

Carotid artery dissection (CAD) is a medical condition where the carotid arteries, which supply blood to the head and neck, become damaged due to tearing or rupturing of their inner lining. This can cause a blockage in the flow of blood, leading to symptoms such as sudden severe pain, vision loss, or a transient ischemic attack (TIA).

There are several risk factors for CAD, including smoking, high blood pressure, and a history of previous neck injuries. It is important to recognize these risks and take preventive measures, such as quitting smoking, managing blood pressure, and wearing protective gear during sports or other activities that may lead to injury.

If you suspect you have CAD, it is crucial to seek medical attention immediately. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further damage and reduce the risk of complications.

Diabetes Mellitus is a medical condition that affects the way the body processes glucose, or sugar. It can be caused by problems with insulin production and/or how the body responds to insulin. It can also be caused by other conditions such as genetics, obesity, and physical inactivity.
Diabetes Mellitus is a metabolic disorder that occurs when the pancreas does not produce enough insulin or when the cells of the body do not respond properly to insulin. This leads to an increase in blood glucose levels.
Diabetes Mellitus is a disease characterized by high blood sugar levels, polyuria and polydipsia, which can lead to various complications if left untreated. It is important for those with diabetes to manage their condition through proper diet, exercise, and medication.

Type 2 diabetes mellitus is a type of diabetes that is characterized by high blood sugar, insulin resistance, and relative lack of insulin. It is also known as non-insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus (NIDDM), insulin resistance, and type II diabetes mellitus.

User, brain disease is not exactly the same as something that is the intersection of a disease and at least one specific location in the brain. Instead, it refers to any central nervous system disorder or dysfunction that occurs within the brain.
Central nervous system diseases can occur in various locations, including the brainstem, cerebellum, cerebral cortex, and spinal cord, as well as other regions of the body. There are many different types of central nervous system diseases, which can be classified based on their location or their underlying cause.
For example, there are neurological disorders such as stroke, traumatic brain injury, epilepsy, and Alzheimer's disease that primarily affect the brain. Similarly, spinal cord injuries and multiple sclerosis can also impact the central nervous system but do not necessarily involve a specific location within the brain.
In conclusion, while there are many different types of brain diseases or disorders, they generally refer to any dysfunction or disruption that occurs in the central nervous system, which encompasses the brain and spinal cord.

Intrinsic asthma is a type of chronic asthma that is triggered by factors not attributable to allergies. It does not have any specific symptoms, but it can cause some anxiety and hyperventilation in those affected. The exact synonym for intrinsic asthma is non-atopic asthma.

status asthmaticus is a type of acute asthma that is characterized by an acute episode with progressive severity, which is poorly responsive to standard therapeutic measures, regardless of the disease severity or phenotypic variant. Another name for status asthmaticus is asthma with status asthmaticus, and it can also be referred to as a severe asthma attack.

vesiculitis is an inflammation of the seminal vesicles, which are small glandular structures located in the male reproductive system that produce semen. It can cause pain and swelling in the scrotum and may affect a man's ability to ejaculate. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and anti-inflammatory medications.

Orbital plasma cell granuloma is a type of chronic inflammation in the orbit, characterized by the accumulation of plasma cells in the tissues around the eye. It can cause symptoms such as swelling and pain, and may also affect vision if it involves the optic nerve or other visual structures. Treatment options vary depending on the severity and location of the inflammation, but may include steroids, immunosuppressants, or other medications to reduce inflammation and manage symptoms. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove affected tissue or relieve pressure on the eye.
Postural kyphosis is a type of kyphosis that occurs due to poor posture, resulting in the stretching of spinal ligament and abnormal formation in the vertebra.

Fuchs heterochromic uveitis is a type of syndrome that affects the eyes. It is characterized by chronic iridocyclitis, which appears as a triad of heterochromia (a condition where the eye's colored part, the iris, changes color), pred

Glaucomatocyclitic crisis is a condition characterized by inflammation of the iris and ciliary body, resulting in increased intraocular pressure. It can also cause pain, redness, and blurred vision. The exact synonyms for this condition are Posner-Schlossman syndrome and Terrien-Viel syndrome.

Iridocyclitis is a type of inflammation that affects the iris and ciliary body in the eye. It is also known as anterior uveitis. The exact synonym for this condition is "primary iridocyclitis," and it can be matched with MESH code D015863.

Gonococcal iridocyclitis is a type of inflammation that occurs in the eyes, typically affecting one eye at a time. It is caused by infection with Neisseria gonorrhoeae, a bacterium that can also cause other types of sexually transmitted infections (STIs). The symptoms of gonococcal iridocyclitis include pain or discomfort in the affected eye, sensitivity to light, redness or swelling around the eye, and excessive tearing. If left untreated, it can lead to permanent damage to the eye. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience these symptoms, as gonococcal iridocyclitis is treatable with antibiotics.

Infectious Anterior Uveitis, also known as iridocyclitis or infectious secondary uveitis, is an inflammatory condition involving the iris and ciliary body of the eye. It occurs when the immune system attacks bacteria that are present in the eye, causing inflammation and pain. The symptoms of Infectious Anterior Uveitis include redness, discomfort, light sensitivity, and blurred vision. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to combat the infection and anti-inflammatory medications to reduce inflammation and pain. In some cases, steroids may also be used to reduce inflammation.

Tracheitis is a type of tracheal disease characterized by symptoms such as cough and high fever. It is caused by bacterial infection, often following a viral upper respiratory infection. The disease can be acute or chronic, with the latter being more persistent. Tracheitis has exact synonyms for its description including acute tracheitis and chronic tracheitis, and it matches MESH code D014136.

Croup is a type of respiratory system disease that is characterized by episodes of difficult breathing and a hoarse, metallic cough. It is caused by various viruses and bacteria, as well as allergies and inhaled irritants. Croup can be caused by parainfluenza virus (types 1 and 2), Influenza A and B viruses, Measles virus, adenovirus, respiratory syncytial virus, Staphylococcus and Streptococcus. It is also known as Croup syndrome, Laryngotracheobronchitis, acute Obstructive Laryngitis, or acute laryngotracheobronchitis.

Acute laryngitis is a short-term inflammation of the larynx, commonly caused by infections or viruses such as the common cold or the flu. Symptoms can include hoarseness, raspy voice, and difficulty swallowing. It typically lasts for a few days to a week, and treatment may involve resting your voice, staying hydrated, and using over-the-counter medications such as throat lozenges or decongestants. In severe cases, medical attention may be necessary.

Epiglottitis is a serious condition that requires prompt medical attention. The symptoms you've described, such as fever, difficulty swallowing, drooling, hoarseness, and stridor, indicate that the epiglottis has become inflamed and may be obstructing the airway. This can make it difficult for the child to breathe and may require hospitalization for treatment with antibiotics and other medications. It's important to seek medical help immediately if you suspect your child has epiglottitis, as prompt treatment can prevent serious complications such as respiratory failure or even death.

Treatment for hypopituitarism typically involves replacing the missing hormones with synthetic versions to help restore normal bodily functions.

Panhypopituitarism is a type of hypopituitarism characterized by the deficiency of at least two pituitary hormones. It was first described by Sir Charles Simmonds in 1902, and it has since been recognized as an important cause of short stature and other growth abnormalities in children.

Panhypopituitarism can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic conditions, infections, tumors, trauma, and radiation therapy. In some cases, the cause may not be identified. Treatment for panhypopituitarism typically involves the replacement of the deficient hormones with synthetic versions to help restore normal growth and development.

It is important for individuals with panhypopituitarism to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage their condition effectively and ensure optimal growth and development. With proper treatment and care, children with panhypopituitarism can lead normal, healthy lives.

allergic asthma is a type of respiratory allergy. It's characterized by symptoms such as coughing, wheezing, shortness of breath and chest tightness, which are triggered by an allergic reaction to inhaled allergens like dust mite, pet dander, pollen and mold.

Blepharitis is a condition that affects the eyelids and can cause discomfort, irritation, and inflammation. Blepharitis can be caused by various factors such as bacterial or viral infections, allergies, or dryness of the eye. It is important to consult an eye doctor if you experience symptoms of blepharitis, as it can lead to more serious conditions if left untreated.

Dientamoebiasis is a parasitic protozoa infectious disease caused by the infection of the large intestine with Dientamoeba fragilis. Symptoms include diarrhea, stomach pain and cramping, loss of appetite and weight, nausea, and fatigue.

Uterine corpus cancer is a type of uterine cancer that occurs in the uterine corpus, which is the central part of the uterus where a baby grows during pregnancy. It is one of the three main types of uterine cancer, along with endometrial cancer and uterine sarcoma. Uterine corpus cancer can be treated with surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy, among other options. It is important to consult a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Exposure keratitis is a type of keratoconjunctivitis that occurs due to prolonged exposure to sunlight or other bright light sources. It is characterized by inflammation and dryness of the cornea, which can cause discomfort, pain, and blurred vision. Other symptoms may include sensitivity to light, redness of the eyes, and a gritty feeling in them. Exposure keratitis can be prevented or treated with proper eye protection, such as sunglasses and hats, and by avoiding prolonged exposure to bright light sources. In severe cases, medications may be prescribed to help manage the symptoms.

cholesteatoma of external ear is a condition where the squamous tissue in the external ear canal becomes infected or inflamed, causing it to erode and create a pocket-like structure. This can lead to the development of cholesteatoma, which is characterized by the growth of skin cells within the eroded area. Cholesteatoma of the external ear can be caused by factors such as infection, trauma or surgery, but it can also develop spontaneously. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have cholesteatoma of the external ear, as it can lead to complications such as deafness and facial disfigurement if left untreated.

That's correct! Otitis externa, also known as swimmer's ear, is an external ear disease that involves inflammation of the outer ear and ear canal. It can be caused by active bacterial or fungal infections, and it is often associated with exposure to water.

Nail patella syndrome, also known as Fong disease and Turner-Kiser syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the development of nails and kneecaps. It is characterized by nail dysplasia, where the nails are abnormally shaped or grow incorrectly, and absent or hypoplastic patellae, which are small or underdeveloped kneecaps. The syndrome has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the LMX1B gene on chromosome 9q33.3. It is an autosomal dominant disease, meaning that a person with one copy of the gene is enough to cause the disorder.

Bacterial meningitis is an inflammation of the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord (meninges) caused by bacteria. It is a serious medical condition that requires prompt treatment, often in a hospital setting. Symptoms may include fever, headache, stiff neck, nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light. In severe cases, it can lead to permanent damage or even death if not treated promptly. Prevention includes vaccinations such as the Bacterial Meningitis vaccine (also known as a meningococcal vaccine) and good hygiene practices such as washing hands regularly with soap and water, especially after being in close contact with sick people or touching surfaces that may contain bacteria.

Meningitis is a type of central nervous system disease that causes inflammation in the meninges, which are the protective membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. It can be caused by bacterial, fungal or viral infections, as well as other conditions such as autoimmune disorders. Symptoms of meningitis may include fever, headache, stiff neck, vomiting, and confusion or difficulty sleeping. In severe cases, it can lead to permanent damage to the brain or spinal cord if not treated promptly. It is important to seek medical attention immediately if you suspect that you or someone you know has meningitis.

Mononeuritis of the lower limbs, also known as peripheral neuropathy, is a type of mononeuritis that affects the nerves in the lower extremities. It occurs when the blood vessels that supply the nerves become narrowed or blocked, causing reduced blood flow and nerve damage. This can lead to symptoms such as numbness, tingling, weakness, and pain in the legs and feet. There are several causes of mononeuritis of the lower limbs, including diabetes, traumatic injuries, autoimmune disorders, and compression of the nerves due to pressure from nearby body structures. Treatment options may include medication to manage pain and improve nerve function, as well as physical therapy to help improve strength and mobility.

Sheehan syndrome is a condition in which the pituitary gland does not produce enough hormones. It is also known as postpartum hypopituitarism, and it can occur when the pituitary gland is damaged due to blood loss or trauma after childbirth. Symptoms of Sheehan syndrome may include fatigue, weakness, excessive thirst, and breastfeeding difficulties. Treatment typically involves replacement therapy with hormones such as desmopressin, thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH), and corticotropin.

Pulmonary embolism is a condition in which a blood clot or other substance blocks the main artery of the lung or one of its branches. This can lead to shortness of breath, chest pain, and other symptoms. It is often treated with medication to dissolve the clot or prevent new ones from forming. In severe cases, it may require surgery to remove the clot or a procedure called thrombolysis to break up the clot. With proper treatment, the outlook for pulmonary embolism is generally good.

Disseminated Eosinophilic Collagen Disease, also known as Hypereosinophilic Syndrome (HES), is a type of collagen disease characterized by the accumulation of eosinophils in various tissues and organs of the body. HES can affect multiple organ systems, including the skin, joints, lungs, gastrointestinal tract, and cardiovascular system.
HES is a rare condition that occurs when the body produces too many eosinophils, which are a type of white blood cell. These elevated levels of eosinophils can cause inflammation and lead to the destruction of tissues and organs over time. Symptoms of HES can vary widely depending on which organs are affected and the severity of the disease. However, some common symptoms include skin rashes or itching, joint pain or stiffness, chest pain or shortness of breath, gastrointestinal issues such as diarrhea or abdominal pain, and cardiovascular problems like heart palpitations or fluttering in the chest.
Diagnosis of HES typically involves a combination of blood tests, imaging studies (such as x-rays or CT scans), and biopsies to assess tissue damage. Treatment for HES may include medications to reduce eosinophil levels, corticosteroids to control inflammation, immunosuppressant drugs, and other medications to manage specific symptoms. In severe cases, stem cell transplantation or other treatments may be necessary.
It is important to note that HES can be a serious condition and requires prompt medical attention. Early diagnosis and treatment are critical for managing symptoms and preventing long-term complications.

Leukocyte disease refers to a condition where the number of leukocytes (white blood cells) in the body is either too low or too high, which can lead to various health issues. It can be classified as a hematopoietic system disease since it affects the production and function of white blood cells.
Leukocyte disease may also be referred to as leukemia when the bone marrow produces an abnormal number of immature or cancerous cells, leading to an increased risk of infections and other health problems. It is essential to consult a medical professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Chronic eosinophilic pneumonia (CEP) is a type of interstitial lung disease characterized by the accumulation of eosinophils in the lungs, leading to inflammation and fibrosis. It is considered a rare condition, with an estimated prevalence of 1-2 cases per million people per year.
CEP can be difficult to diagnose due to its nonspecific presentation, which may include shortness of breath, cough, and fever. In some cases, it may also present with asthma-like symptoms or no symptoms at all.
Treatment options for CEP typically involve a combination of corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and bronchodilators. The specific treatment plan will depend on the individual case and the severity of the disease. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you may have CEP or any other form of interstitial lung disease.

Loeffler syndrome is a type of eosinophilic pneumonia that can occur in response to a parasitic infection. It is characterized by mild pneumonitis, transitory pulmonary infiltration, and eosinophilia. Loeffler's pneumonia, also known as Loffler's syndrome, is considered an allergic reaction and is marked by symptoms such as coughing up blood, fever, chills, shortness of breath, and a history of exposure to the parasite that caused the infection.

Benign mammary dysplasia is a type of breast benign neoplasm. Benign mammary dysplasia has the definition "A breast benign neoplasm that encompasses a range of conditions in which there is marked change in the breast tissue."

Cannabis abuse refers to the habitual use of cannabis, often resulting in negative consequences for one's health, relationships, and overall well-being. It is characterized by a compulsive need to use the drug despite its harmful effects and potential legal repercussions. The term "marijuana abuse" is often used interchangeably with cannabis abuse, as both refer to the excessive and problematic use of marijuana or cannabis plants containing THC.

In addition to negative health consequences such as addiction, respiratory problems, and impaired cognitive functioning, cannabis abuse can also lead to social isolation, legal issues, and financial burdens. It is important for individuals struggling with cannabis abuse to seek professional help in order to overcome their addiction and improve their overall quality of life.

acute ethmoiditis is a type of acute sinusitis that affects the ethmoid sinuses. Ethmoid sinusitis is a type of sinusitis that involves an infection of the ethmoid sinuses, located behind and between the eyes. This condition can cause pain or pressure behind the eyes, tearing, headache over the forehead, and other symptoms such as a feeling of fullness in the ears, nasal congestion, and discharge. Ethmoid sinusitis is also sometimes referred to as ethmoidal sinusitis or ethmoiditis.

Latent syphilis is a stage of the syphilis infection where the disease is not active but still present in the body. It is typically diagnosed through serological tests that can detect the presence of antibodies against the Treponema pallidum bacteria, which causes syphilis.
During the latent stage, individuals may not experience any symptoms or feel sick at all. However, if left untreated, it can progress to the next stage, called tertiary syphilis, which can cause severe damage to various organs and systems in the body. Therefore, it is important to seek medical treatment for latent syphilis to prevent further complications.

Tuberculous pneumothorax is a specific type of pneumothorax that occurs due to the presence of tuberculosis (TB) bacteria in the pleural cavity. This leads to the accumulation of air in the pleural space, causing the typical symptoms of chest pain, shortness of breath, and coughing up blood. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you may have tuberculous pneumothorax, as it requires prompt treatment with antibiotics and other medications to prevent further complications or death.

Lassa fever is a viral infectious disease that results from the infection with the Mammarenavirus Lassaense, which is transmitted by multimammate rats of the genus Mastomys. The symptoms include fever, retrosternal pain, sore throat, back pain, cough, abdominal pain, vomiting, diarrhea, conjunctivitis, facial swelling, proteinuria (protein in the urine), and mucosal bleeding.

Multiple myeloma is a type of cancer that affects plasma cells, which are a part of the immune system. It is characterized by the overproduction of antibodies (immunoglobulins) and can lead to problems with blood clotting and bone health. It typically affects older adults and is more common in African Americans than in other racial groups. Treatment options for multiple myeloma may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, stem cell transplantation, and targeted therapies.

Multiple myeloma is a type of blood cancer that affects plasma cells, which are a part of the immune system and are responsible for producing antibodies that help fight infections and diseases. Adrenal gland disease refers to a condition that affects the adrenal glands, which are located on top of the kidneys. The adrenal glands produce hormones that regulate various bodily functions, such as blood pressure and metabolism. When these glands become diseased or damaged, it can lead to a range of health problems.

Adrenal gland disease is considered an endocrine system disease because it involves the disruption of hormone production by the adrenal glands. There are several types of adrenal gland disease, including Addison's disease, Cushing's disease, and Conn's syndrome. Each type has its own specific causes and symptoms, but generally speaking, adrenal gland diseases can cause a range of symptoms related to hormone imbalances, such as fatigue, weakness, weight loss, and high blood pressure.

Treatment for adrenal gland disease depends on the specific type and severity of the disease. In some cases, medication may be used to replace or regulate hormone production, while in other cases, surgery may be necessary to remove affected gland tissue. It's important to work with a healthcare provider to determine the best course of treatment for your specific case of adrenal gland disease.
